{"title_page": "Silver Line (MBTA)", "text_new": "{{short description|Boston bus line}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox Bus transit\n| name            = MBTA Silver Line\n| image           = MBTA route SLW bus approaching World Trade Center station, March 2017.JPG\n| image_size      = 320px\n| image_caption   = A Silver Line bus approaching World Trade Center station\n| parent          = [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]\n| founded         = July 20, 2002 (Washington Street)<br>December 17, 2004 (Waterfront)\n| locale          = [[Boston]] and [[Chelsea, Massachusetts|Chelsea]], [[Massachusetts]]\n| service_type    = [[Bus rapid transit]] (disputed)\n| routes          = 6\n| stops           = 14 (Washington Street)<br />21 (Waterfront)\n| hubs            = {{bts|South Station Under}}, {{bts|Dudley Square}}\n| fleet           = 24 (Washington Street)<br />32 (Waterfront)\n| ridership       = 39,000 (Q2 2019)<ref name=ridership>{{cite web |url=https://cdn.mbta.com/sites/default/files/2019-10/2019-10-07-fmcb-M-ridership-quarterly-update-accessible.pdf |title=Quarterly Ridership Update |date=October 7, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |page=3 |first=Laura |last=Riegel}}</ref>\n| fuel_type       = [[Hybrid electric bus|Diesel hybrid]] (Washington Street)<br />Dual-mode diesel/[[trolleybus]] (Waterfront)\n| website         = [http://www.mbta.com/schedules/bus MBTA - Bus]\n}}\n\nThe '''Silver Line''' is a system of bus routes in [[Boston]] and [[Chelsea, Massachusetts]] operated by the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] (MBTA). It is operated as part of the [[MBTA Bus]] system, but branded as [[bus rapid transit]] (BRT) as part of the [[MBTA subway]] system. Six routes are operated as part of two disconnected corridors. {{As of|2019}}, weekday ridership on the Silver Line was 39,000.\n\nThe four Waterfront routes operate out of an underground terminal at {{bts|South Station Under}} and run through the South Boston Piers Transitway - a dedicated bus tunnel through the [[Seaport District]] with stations at {{bts|Courthouse}} and {{bts|World Trade Center}} . At {{bts|Silver Line Way}}, they fan out on the surface: the SL1 to [[Logan International Airport]], the SL2 to [[Boston Marine Industrial Park|Design Center]], and the SL3 to {{bts|Chelsea}} via [[East Boston]]. (An additional [[short turn]] route, SLW, runs only at peak hours between South Station and Silver Line Way.) The SL1 and SL3 operate in [[mixed traffic]] through the [[Ted Williams Tunnel]]; the SL3 uses a limited-access [[haul road]] in East Boston and a dedicated busway in Chelsea for part of its route. The SL2 operates in mixed traffic in the Seaport. The Waterfront routes use [[articulated buses|articulated]] [[dual-mode bus]]es that operate as electric [[trolleybus]]es in the Transitway and conventional diesel buses on the surface. Battery electric buses and a diesel hybrid bus with extended battery range are being tested; one of the types may ultimately replace the dual-mode buses.\n\nTwo routes operate on [[Washington Street (Boston)|Washington Street]] between [[Dudley Square station]] (at [[Nubian Square]] in [[Roxbury (Boston)|Roxbury]]) and [[Downtown Boston]]. The SL5 terminates at {{bts|Downtown Crossing}} and the SL4 on the surface at {{bts|South Station Under}}. The two routes operate mostly in [[bus lane|dedicated lanes]] on Washington Street and Essex Street, though sections in Downtown Boston and Nubian Square operate in mixed traffic. They use articulated diesel hybrid buses, which replaced [[compressed natural gas]] (CNG)-powered buses in 2016\u201317.\n\nThe Washington Street corridor was built to replace the [[Orange Line (MBTA)|Orange Line]] [[rapid transit]] line, which was moved from the [[Washington Street Elevated]] to the [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]] in 1987. Initial plans called for a [[light rail]] line operated as part of the [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]], but trolleybuses and later CNG buses were substituted. Service improvements to the route 49 bus began in 2001, and the Silver Line brand was introduced on July 20, 2002. The articulated CNG buses began operation in 2003. On October 13, 2009, the SL4 began service and the original route was designated SL5.\n\nPlanning began in 1987 for mass transit to serve the growing Seaport; a new transit tunnel called the South Boston Piers Transitway was chosen in 1989. It was to run from {{bts|Boylston}} to World Trade Center via {{bts|Chinatown}} and South Station, though the Boylston-South Station section was later deferred as a separate phase. After years of delays, service through the $624 million Transitway began on December 17, 2004. SL2 and SL3 service began on December 31, 2004, with the SL1 added on June 1, 2005. The original SL3 route to {{bts|City Point}} was discontinued on March 20, 2009. A separate SL3 route to Chelsea \u2014 originally planned as part of the cancelled [[Urban Ring Project (MBTA)|Urban Ring Project]] \u2013 began service on April 21, 2018.\n\nIn 1999, the MBTA designated the Washington Street and Transitway projects as the Silver Line, and planned for the Boylston tunnel extension to include a portal to Washington Street for through-running. The connecting tunnel from Washington Street to Boylston was designated as Phase III. After several design changes, by 2005 Phase III was expected to cost around $800 million; projected completion had been delayed from 2006 to 2010, then to 2013. The project was placed on hold in 2005; planning resumed in 2006 after the controversial portal was relocated. However, the project cost rose to $2.1 billion, and it was cancelled in 2010. Several other Silver Line extensions have been proposed, as has a conversion of the Washington Street corridor to light rail, but most have not been pursued.\n\nThe Silver Line has been the target of criticism by riders and transportation planners. The choice of buses rather than light rail on Washington Street was viewed by Roxbury residents as a deliberate slight, leading to the nickname of \"The Silver Lie.\" Much of the Silver Line is missing [[BRT Standard]] features such as enforced dedicated lanes, off-vehicle fare collection, sheltered stations, and [[transit signal priority]]; a 2011 report by the [[Institute for Transportation and Development Policy]] (ITDP) called the Silver Line \"Not BRT\". Because the Transitway was not originally designed for service to Logan Airport or Chelsea, it does not have a direct connection to the Ted Williams Tunnel. A normally-unused ramp would shorten the outbound routing by {{convert|0.7|miles}}; after years of controversy, [[MassDOT]] agreed in 2019 to allow limited use of the ramp.\n\n==Routes==\n{{anchor|Waterfront|SL1|SL2|SL3|SLW}}\n\n===Waterfront: SL1, SL2, SL3===\n{{MBTA Silver Line Waterfront}}\nThree Silver Line services operate from {{bts|South Station Under}} in a dedicated tunnel, the South Boston Piers Transitway, serving the underground {{bts|Courthouse}} and {{bts|World Trade Center}} stations in the [[Seaport District]] then splitting at the {{bts|Silver Line Way}} surface station.\n\n* '''SL1''' Logan Airport \u2013 South Station\n* '''SL2''' Design Center \u2013 South Station\n* '''SL3''' Chelsea \u2013 South Station\nDuring rush hours, additional [[short turn]]s (designated '''SLW''') are run between South Station and Silver Line Way to increase frequency in the Transitway.\n\nRoute SL2 runs on Northern Avenue, then on a one-way loop on Drydock Avenue and Black Falcon Avenue with multiple stops serving the Innovation and Design Building and the [[Port of Boston|Flynn Cruiseport Boston]]. Buses run clockwise around the loop, with a layover at Design Center Place in the morning and 23 Dry Dock Avenue in the afternoon. From Silver Line Way, route SL1 and SL3 buses loop backwards on Haul Road, then cross under [[Boston Harbor]] in the [[Ted Williams Tunnel]] to [[East Boston]]. Route SL1 loops around the [[Logan International Airport]] terminals, with stops at the arrivals level of each terminal (including two separate stops at lengthy Terminal B). Route SL3 serves {{bts|Airport}} station, follows the Coughlin Bypass Road, and crosses [[Chelsea Creek]] on the [[Chelsea Street Bridge]]. It then follows a dedicated busway to {{bts|Chelsea}}, with intermediate stops at {{bts|Eastern Avenue}}, {{bts|Box District}}, and {{bts|Bellingham Square}}.<ref name=busmap /><ref name=netransit /> The three Transitway stops are full rapid transit stations; the Chelsea busway stations have large concrete shelters, while most other surface stops have small shelters.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|10}}\n\nThe Waterfront routes have regular rapid transit fares.<ref name=tariff />{{rp|13}} Passengers enter through faregates at the three Transitway stations, and pay at the on-board farebox at all other stops.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|12}} Fares are free when boarding at the Logan Airport stops.<ref name=tariff />{{rp|31}} (Inbound SL3 fares in Chelsea are also temporarily free during the Tobin Bridge/Chelsea Curves Rehabilitation Project, which is expected to last until late 2020.)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mass.gov/info-details/about-the-tobin-bridgechelsea-curves-rehabilitation-project |title=About the Tobin Bridge/Chelsea Curves Rehabilitation Project |year=2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation}}</ref> Transfer is possible to the Red Line within fare control at South Station. Normal transfers to other routes are available with a CharlieCard; transfers to/from the [[Blue Line (MBTA)|Blue Line]] at Airport and the Washington Street routes are available with a CharlieTicket.<ref name=tariff />{{rp|27}}\n\nThe Waterfront routes primarily use {{convert|60|ft|adj=on}} [[articulated bus]]es with three doors, which provide greater capacity than standard {{convert|40|ft|adj=on}} transit buses. The [[dual-mode bus]]es operate as electric [[trolleybus]]es (similar to the [[Trolleybuses in Greater Boston|older Harvard-based trolleybus system]]) between South Station and Silver Line Way, and as conventional diesel buses on the surface branches.<ref name=roster /> The buses are low-floor and fully [[accessible]], with [[kneeling bus]] technology and a [[wheelchair ramp]] at the front door. The 32 dual-mode buses, built by [[Neoplan USA]], were delivered in 2004-05 and overhauled in 2014\u201318.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://bangordailynews.com/2018/0/28/news/aroostock/mma-completes-mbta-bus-contract-releases-more-than-50-employees-2/ |newspaper=Bangor Daily News |title=MMA completes MBTA bus contract, releases more than 50 employees |date=August 28, 2018 |first=Christopher |last=Bouchard}}</ref><ref name=2007report />{{rp|11}} Eight of the buses were funded by [[Massport]] and include luggage racks for airport passengers.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|11}} All Silver Line buses are maintained at Southampton Street Garage.<ref name=roster>{{cite web |url=http://www.transithistory.org/roster/ |title=The MBTA Vehicle Inventory Page |publisher=NETransit |accessdate=October 9, 2019}}</ref><ref name=2005report />{{rp|2.8}}\n\nThe existing dual-mode service pattern requires difficult-to-maintain dual-mode buses, and buses must make a time-consuming switch between modes at Silver Line Way.<ref name=ITDP /> Additionally, the [[overhead lines]] in the Transitway are difficult to maintain.<ref name=stateofthesystem>{{cite web |url=https://www.mbtafocus40.com/s/Bus-SoS-Report-Final-Accessible_121815.pdf |title=State of the System: Bus |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=December 2015 |pages=28, 39\u201340}}</ref> The MBTA has obtained several buses to test alternate options for Waterfront service. A single [[New Flyer]] [[hybrid electric bus|diesel hybrid bus]] with extended battery range - sufficient to run through the Transitway on battery power - was obtained as an option on a separate order; it entered testing in September 2018 and revenue service in December. If that bus is deemed successful, the MBTA could order up to 45 similar buses.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2018-09-26/first-extended-range-hybrid-bus-joins-mbta-silver-line-fleet |title=First Extended-range Hybrid Bus Joins MBTA Silver Line Fleet |date=September 26, 2018 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=MBTA Vehicle Inventory as of February 28, 2019 |first=Jonathan |last=Belcher |date=January\u2013February 2019 |magazine=Rollsign |volume=56 |issue=1/2 |page=19}}</ref> On July 31, 2019, the MBTA began using five New Flyer [[battery electric bus]]es on both Waterfront and Washington Street routes.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2019-07-31/first-zero-emission-battery-electric-buses-join-the-mbta-silver-line-fleet |title=First Zero-emission, Battery-electric Buses Join the MBTA Silver Line Fleet |date=July 31, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n{{anchor|Waterfront stops|Waterfront stop listing}}\n\n====Stop listing====\n[[File:Power changeover at Silver Line Way inbound, March 2016.JPG|thumb|right|The power changeover at Silver Line Way]]\n[[File:MBTA route SL2 bus on Black Falcon Avenue, June 2017.JPG|thumb|right|An SL2 bus on Black Falcon Avenue]]\n[[File:MBTA route SL3 bus at Airport Station, December 2018.JPG|thumb|right|An SL3 bus at Airport station]]\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Neighborhood\n!rowspan=2|Station\n!colspan=4|Services\n!rowspan=2|Service began\n!rowspan=2|Transfers and notes\n|-\n!SL1\n!SL2\n!SL3\n!SLW\n|-\n|[[Financial District (Boston)|Financial District]]\n|{{bts|South Station}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|rowspan=4|December 17, 2004\n|{{rint|us|Amtrak}} [[Amtrak]]: {{lnl|Amtrak|Acela Express}}, {{lnl|Amtrak|Lake Shore Limited}}, {{lnl|Amtrak|Northeast Regional}}<br>{{rint|Boston|rail}} [[MBTA Commuter Rail]]: [[Fairmount Line|Fairmount]], [[Framingham/Worcester Line|Framingham/Worcester]], [[Franklin Line|Franklin]], [[Greenbush Line|Greenbush]], [[Needham Line|Needham]], [[Old Colony Lines|Old Colony]], and [[Providence/Stoughton Line|Providence/Stoughton]] lines; [[CapeFLYER]] (seasonal)<br>{{rint|Boston|subway}} [[MBTA subway]]: [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red Line]], Silver Line ({{MBTABus|SL4}})<br>{{bus icon}} [[MBTA Bus]]: {{MBTABus|4|7|11}}<br>{{bus icon}} Intercity buses at [[South Station Bus Terminal]]\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Seaport District]]\n|{{bts|Courthouse}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|4}}\n|-\n|{{bts|World Trade Center}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|4}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Silver Line Way}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|Changeover point between [[Diesel engine|diesel]] and [[Overhead lines|overhead electric]] power (except SLW)\n|-\n|rowspan=6|[[East Boston]]\n|{{bts|Terminal A}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|\n|rowspan=5|June 1, 2005\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus {{MBTABus|171}}<br>{{bus icon}} [[Massachusetts Port Authority#Massport Shuttle|Massport Shuttle]]: 11, 22, 55, 66, 88\n|-\n|{{bts|Terminal B Stop 1}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus {{MBTABus|171}}<br>{{bus icon}} Massport Shuttle: 11, 22, 55, 66, 88\n|-\n|{{bts|Terminal B Stop 2}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus {{MBTABus|171}}<br>{{bus icon}} Massport Shuttle: 11, 22, 55, 66, 88\n|-\n|{{bts|Terminal C}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus {{MBTABus|171}}<br>{{bus icon}} Massport Shuttle: 11, 33, 55, 66, 88\n|-\n|{{bts|Terminal E}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus {{MBTABus|171}}<br>{{bus icon}} Massport Shuttle: 11, 33, 55, 66, 88\n|-\n|{{bts|Airport}}\n|\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|rowspan=5|April 21, 2018\n|{{rint|subway}} MBTA subway: [[Blue Line (MBTA)|Blue Line]]<br>{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus {{MBTABus|171}}<br>{{bus icon}} Massport Shuttle: 22, 33, 55, 66\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Chelsea, Massachusetts|Chelsea]]\n|{{bts|Eastern Avenue}}\n|\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|112}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Box District}}\n|\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{bts|Bellingham Square}}\n|\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|{{rint|boston|rail}} MBTA Commuter Rail: [[Newburyport/Rockport Line]] (planned move to Chelsea in late 2021<ref name=chelsea-commuter/>)<br>{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|111|112|114|116|117}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Chelsea}}\n|\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|112}}, {{MBTABus|114}}<br>Newburyport/Rockport Line station to open in late 2021<ref name=chelsea-commuter/>\n|-\n|rowspan=6|South Boston\n|Northern Avenue & Harbor Street\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|rowspan=2|December 31, 2004\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|4}}\n|-\n|Northern Avenue & Tide Street\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|4}}\n|-\n|23 Drydock Avenue\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|{{circa|2006}}<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060110200931/http://www.mbta.com:80/traveling_t/pdf/system/dt3_southboston.pdf |archivedate=January 10, 2006 |url=http://www.mbta.com:80/traveling_t/pdf/system/dt3_southboston.pdf |title=MBTA Downtown Map [Downtown Boston quadrant] |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |first=Kenneth A. |last=Dumas |year=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060221110856/http://www.mbta.com:80/traveling_t/pdf/system/dt3_southboston.pdf |archivedate=February 21, 2006 |url=http://www.mbta.com:80/traveling_t/pdf/system/dt3_southboston.pdf |title=MBTA Downtown Map [Downtown Boston quadrant] |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |first=Kenneth A. |last=Dumas |year=2006}}</ref><!-- http://web.archive.org/web/20051230130902/http://www.mbta.com/traveling_t/schedules_pdfmaps_downtown.asp# -->\n|Relocated from 21 Drydock Avenue in 2016<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160522171604/http://www.mbta.com/rider_tools/transit_updates/?ttype=bus&atype=alert&route=SL2&detail=SL2 |archivedate=May 22, 2016 |url=http://www.mbta.com/rider_tools/transit_updates/?ttype=bus&atype=alert&route=SL2&detail=SL2 |date=April 27, 2016 |title=Bus Service Alerts: SL2 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n|-\n|27 Drydock Avenue\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|rowspan=3|December 31, 2004\n|Former stop at 25 Drydock Avenue closed in January 2016, relocated stop opened 2018<!--first source has relocated to 27DD in 2016, but that was actually the DD&BF corner stop. GTFS says September 2018; maps say December.--><ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423091718/http://www.mbta.com/rider_tools/transit_updates/?ttype=bus&atype=alert&route=SL2&detail=SL2 |archivedate=April 23, 2016 |url=http://www.mbta.com/rider_tools/transit_updates/?ttype=bus&atype=alert&route=SL2&detail=SL2 |date=January 3, 2016 |title=Bus Service Alerts: SL2 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref><ref name=sept2018map>{{cite web |title=Silver Line SL1\u2022SL2\u2022SL3 Effective September 2, 2018 |url=https://cdn.mbta.com/sites/default/files/route_pdfs/2018-fall/rtSilver1-3.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818121347/https://cdn.mbta.com/sites/default/files/route_pdfs/2018-fall/rtSilver1-3.pdf |archivedate=August 18, 2018 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=September 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=dec2018map>{{cite web |title=Silver Line SL1\u2022SL2\u2022SL3 Effective December 23, 2018 |url=https://cdn.mbta.com/sites/default/files/route_pdfs/2019-winter/rtSilver1-3.pdf |date=December 23, 2018 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n|-\n|Drydock Avenue & Black Falcon Avenue\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|Replacement stop for 88 Black Falcon Avenue during nights and poor weather until January 2016; official stop since 2018<ref name=sept2018map /><ref name=dec2018map /><!--GTFS has it as a full-time stop beginning September 3, 2016; however, it appears it was used beginning in January when 25DD was closed.-->\n|-\n|Design Center\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|4}}\n\n|}\n\n====Former stops====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Neighborhood\n!Station\n!Served by\n!Service began\n!Service ended\n!Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=6|South Boston\n|88 Black Falcon Avenue\n|SL2\n|rowspan=5|December 31, 2004\n|April 2019\n|Temporarily closed in April 2019 due to pier repair; permanent closure is planned.<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001191212/https://mbta.com/alerts/bus |archivedate=October 1, 2019 |url=https://mbta.com/alerts/bus |date=April 27, 2019 |title=SL2 Design Center - South Station |work=Alerts |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://mbta.com/projects/better-bus-project/update/board-approves-36-bus-route-updates |title=Board Approves 36 Bus Route Updates |date=May 6, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n|-\n|Black Falcon Avenue & Design Center Place\n|SL2\n|2014\n|\n|-\n|Summer Street & Powerhouse Street\n|SL3\n|rowspan=3|March 20, 2009\n|Discontinued due to low ridership<ref name=netransit />\n|-\n|East 1st Street & M Street\n|SL3\n|Discontinued due to low ridership<ref name=netransit />\n|-\n|{{bts|City Point}}\n|SL3\n|Discontinued due to low ridership<ref name=netransit />\n|-\n|Farragut Road\n|SL3\n|April 9, 2005<ref name=netransit />\n|August 20, 2005\n|Rerouted due to noise complaints<ref name=2008serviceplan />\n|}\n\n{{anchor|Washington Street|SL4|SL5}}\n\n===Washington Street: SL4 and SL5===\n{{MBTA Silver Line Washington Street}}\nTwo Silver Line route run between [[Dudley Square station]] (at [[Nubian Square]] in [[Roxbury (Boston)|Roxbury]]) and [[Downtown Boston]] along [[Washington Street (Boston)|Washington Street]]:\n* '''SL4''' Dudley Square \u2013 South Station\n* '''SL5''' Dudley Square \u2013 Downtown Crossing\n\nThese two route share most of their routing on Washington Street between Nubian Square and {{bts|Tufts Medical Center}}, with dedicated lanes for most of the corridor and eight intermediate stops. North of Kneeland Street, the routes run on separate one-way loops. The SL5 runs north on Washington Street to Template Place (between {{bts|Downtown Crossing}} and {{bts|Park Street}}, with an intermediate stop at {{bts|Chinatown}}. It returns south on [[Tremont Street]], with a southbound stop at {{bts|Boylston}}. The SL4 runs north on Washington Street to Chinatown, then east on Essex Street (with a dedicated lane) to a surface stop at {{bts|South Station Under}}. It returns south on Surface Road and Kneeland Street.<ref name=busmap>{{cite web |url=https://mbta.com/bus-map |title=System Map |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref> Most stops have a canopy shelter with seating, maps, and a real-time arrival information display.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|2.5}}\n\nThe two routes have the [[MBTA#fares|same fare]] as local bus services (lower than rapid transit), with normal transfers with a [[CharlieCard]].<ref name=tariff>{{cite web |url=https://cdn.mbta.com/sites/default/files/fares/2019-06-28-mbta-and-cr-tariff-effective-20190701.pdf |title=MBTA Tariff and Statement of Fare and Transfer Rules |date=July 1, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>{{rp|14}} In recognition of their role as replacement for the Orange Line, transfers are also available with a paper CharlieTicket (which normally does not allow transfers).<ref name=tariff />{{rp|27}} This was inherited from the previous route 49 bus, which had free transfers (with the flat [[token coin|token]] fare) to/from the Orange Line only at {{bts|New England Medical Center}}.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|2.9}}\n\nThe Washington Street routes use {{convert|60|ft|adj=on}} [[Hybrid electric bus|diesel hybrid]] [[articulated bus]]es with three doors, which provide greater capacity than standard {{convert|40|ft|adj=on}} transit buses.<ref name=roster />  The buses are low-floor and fully [[accessible]], with [[kneeling bus]] technology and a [[wheelchair ramp]] at the front door. The routes use 21 [[New Flyer]] XDE60 buses delivered in 2016-17 (part of a 44-bus order also used on routes {{MBTABus|28}} and {{MBTABus|39}}), which replaced the original [[compressed natural gas]] (CNG) buses, as well as 3 [[New Flyer]] DE60LFR's delivered in 2010 (part of a small 24-bus order, also used on routes 28/39)<ref name=roster /><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2015-10-06/mbta-purchases-dozens-new-high-capacity-buses |title=MBTA Purchases Dozens of New, High Capacity Buses |date=October 6, 2015 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref> All Silver Line buses are maintained at Southampton Street Garage.<ref name=roster /><ref name=2005report />{{rp|2.8}}\n\n{{anchor|Washington Street stop listing|Washington Street stops}}\n\n====Stop listing====\n[[File:MBTA route SL5 bus on Washington Street, April 2017.jpg|thumb|right|An SL5 bus near Herald Street]]\n[[File:Southbound shelter at Melnea Cass Boulevard station, July 2019.JPG|thumb|right|Melnea Cass Boulevard, a typical Washington Street stop]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=2|Neighborhood\n!rowspan=2|Station\n!colspan=2|Services\n!rowspan=2|Service began\n!rowspan=2|Transfers and notes\n|-\n!SL4\n!SL5\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Roxbury, Boston|Roxbury]]\n|{{bts|Dudley Square}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|rowspan=4|July 20, 2002<ref name=netransit/>\n|{{bus icon}} [[MBTA Bus]]: {{MBTABus|1|8|14|15|19|23|28|41|42|44|45|47|66|170|171|191}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Melnea Cass Boulevard}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|1|8|19|47|170|171|191|CT3}}\n|-\n|rowspan=7|[[South End, Boston|South End]]\n|{{bts|Lenox Street}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|8|170|191}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Massachusetts Avenue|Silver}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|1|8|170|191}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Worcester Square}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|November 2002<ref name=2005report/>{{rp|3.2}}\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|8|170|191}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Newton Street}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|rowspan=8|July 20, 2002<ref name=netransit/>\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|8|10|170|191}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Union Park Street}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|10|191}}\n|-\n|{{bts|East Berkeley Street}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|9|11|191}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Herald Street}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|9|11|191}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Chinatown, Boston|Chinatown]]\n|{{bts|Tufts Medical Center}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{rint|subway}} [[MBTA subway]]: [[Orange Line (MBTA)|Orange Line]]<br>{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|11|43|191}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Chinatown}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{rint|subway}} MBTA subway: Orange Line<br>{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|11|191}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Downtown Boston]]\n|{{bts|Downtown Crossing}}\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{rint|subway}} MBTA subway: [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green]], Orange, and [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red]] lines<br>{{bus icon|12px}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|7|11|43|55|191|192|193|501|504|505|553|554|556|558}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Boylston}}\n|\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{rint|subway}} MBTA subway: Green Line<br>{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|43|55|191|192|193}}\n|-\n|{{bts|South Station Under}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|October 13, 2009<ref name=netransit/>\n|{{rint|us|Amtrak}} [[Amtrak]]: {{lnl|Amtrak|Acela Express}}, {{lnl|Amtrak|Lake Shore Limited}}, {{lnl|Amtrak|Northeast Regional}}<br>{{rint|Boston|rail}} [[MBTA Commuter Rail]]: [[Fairmount Line|Fairmount]], [[Framingham/Worcester Line|Framingham/Worcester]], [[Franklin Line|Franklin]], [[Greenbush Line|Greenbush]], [[Needham Line|Needham]], [[Old Colony Lines|Old Colony]], and [[Providence/Stoughton Line|Providence/Stoughton]] lines; [[CapeFLYER]] (seasonal)<br>{{rint|Boston|subway}} MBTA subway: Red Line, Silver Line ({{MBTABus|SL1|SL2|SL3}})<br>{{bus icon}} [[MBTA Bus]]: {{MBTABus|4|7|11}}<br>{{bus icon}} Intercity buses at [[South Station Bus Terminal]]\n|}\n\n==History==\n===Washington Street development===\n[[File:Removal of Northampton station headhouse, 1987.jpg|thumb|right|Removal of the Elevated in 1987]]\nThe 1947 state act that created the [[Metropolitan Transit Authority (Boston)|Metropolitan Transit Authority]] (MTA) from the [[Boston Elevated Railway]] established four immediate projects for the new agency: extension of rapid transit to {{bts|Braintree}}, expansion of the [[Tremont Street Subway]] to four tracks, replacement of the existing elevated lines ([[Charlestown Elevated]], [[Causeway Street Elevated]], and [[Washington Street Elevated]]) with subways, and an extension of the [[Red Line (MBTA)|Cambridge-Dorchester Line]] northwest from {{bts|Harvard}}.<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/actsresolvespass1947mass/page/538 |title=Acts and Resolves passed by the General Court of Massachusetts in the year 1947 |chapter=Chapter 544: An act providing for the creation of the Metropolitan Transit Authority and the acquisition and operation by it of the entire assets, property and franchises of the Boston Elevated Railway Company |pages=539\u2013556 |date=June 19, 1947 |publisher=Secretary of the Commonwealth |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> In 1948, the legislature authorized the city to issue $19 million in bonds (equivalent to ${{format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|19000000|1948}}}} in {{Inflation/year|US}}) to construct an extension of the [[Washington Street Tunnel (Boston)|Washington Street Tunnel]] under Shawmut Street, connecting with the existing elevated south of Dudley Square.<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/actsresolvespass1948mass/page/692 |title=Acts and Resolves passed by the General Court of Massachusetts in the year 1948 |chapter=Chapter 622: An act providing for certain rapid transit improvements in the City of Boston |pages=693\u2013702 |date=June 15, 1948 |publisher=Secretary of the Commonwealth |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> Although none of the proposals were built immediately, it established a precedent of replacing the elevated lines. In 1972, [[Highway revolts in the United States#Massachusetts|protests]] led to cancellation of the planned [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Expressway]]. Instead, the alignment was used for [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|a combined corridor]] for intercity rail, commuter rail, and the [[Orange Line (MBTA)|Orange Line]] - replacing the Washington Street Elevated of the latter.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|3.1}}\n\nThe northern part of the new corridor was about {{convert|1/2|mile}} west of Washington Street, so the MBTA began planning in 1978 for a replacement service between Dudley Square and Downtown Boston.<ref>{{cite report |url=https://archive.org/details/replacementtrans1978mass |title=Replacement / transit improvement study: South End / Roxbury / Dorchester / Mattapan: Phase I Feasibility Report |year=1978 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |via=Internet Archive}}</ref><ref name=2005report />{{rp|3.1}} By 1985, the MBTA favored bus or [[light rail]] service on Washington Street; the latter would have been a branch of the [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]], operated through [[Pleasant Street Portal|the 1962-abandoned southern branch]].<ref>{{cite report |url=https://archive.org/details/replacementtrans00cbtc |title=Replacement / transit improvement study: South End / Roxbury / Dorchester / Mattapan: What's happened... and what's happening next? |year=1985 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> The Orange Line was rerouted in 1987; that year, [[Federal Transit Administration|UMTA]] rejected the MBTA's funding request to create a [[light rail]] line on the corridor.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|3.1}} Local opinion favored the temporary retention of the northern portion of the Elevated until a permanent replacement could be built.<ref name=orangelinebook>{{cite book |title=When Boston Rode The El |last1=Cheney |first1=Frank |last2=Sammarco |first2=Anthony M. |year=2000 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |isbn=9780738504629 |page=9}}</ref> However, the MBTA closed the Elevated and instead upgraded the route 49 bus from a feeder route to a more frequent trunk route.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|3.1}}\n[[File:MBTA Silver Line logo.png|thumb|left|The MBTA used this logo to advertise the Silver Line]]\nIn 1989, the MBTA announced that [[trolleybuses]] would be used on Washington Street, operating on 4-minute headways at peak hours.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|3.1}} By 1990, the MBTA expected service to begin in 1993, with an underground connection to [[Boylston station]] and the proposed South Boston Piers tunnel in a future phase.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/trolleybusesonwa00mass |title=Trolley buses on Washington Street! |date=October 1990 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> After several more years of studies, the MBTA decided in 1996-97 to build the route as a [[bus rapid transit]] line using [[compressed natural gas]] (CNG) buses to avoid the visual impact of overhead wires.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|3.2}} Environmental documentation was filed in 1998, and construction began in 2001.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|3.2}} The project cost $27.3 million, with major elements including $10.9 million for the 17 new buses, $10.9 million for road work, and $2.6 million for shelters.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|2.14}} Planning and construction were combined with a necessary repaving of Washington Street, reducing costs.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|5.8}} Intended for the route to equal the service quality of light rail, the MBTA branded it as the \"Silver Line\" and designated it equally to the existing [[MBTA subway]] lines on maps.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|4.11}}\n\nThe Silver Line followed largely the same route between {{bts|Dudley Square}} and Downtown Boston as route 49; the primary change was stop consolidation.<ref name=netransit /> (Although the MBTA considered other stop locations, most of the final stops were at existing route 49 stops.)<ref name=2005report />{{rp|3.3}} The conversion to the Silver Line occurred in several steps. In December 2001, the MBTA opened a [[contraflow]] bus-only lane on Washington Street between Marginal Street and East Berkeley Street, allowing southbound buses to use Washington Street. This eliminated a longer outbound routing via Surface Road, and allowed an extension to a new downtown terminal at Temple Place (between {{bts|Park Street}} and {{bts|Downtown Crossing}} stations). Service frequency was also increased at that time.<ref name=2005report>{{cite report |url=https://nbrti.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/Boston_Silver_Line_final_report.pdf |title=Boston Silver Line Washington Street Bus Rapid Transit (BRT): Demonstration Project Evaluation |first1=Paul |last1=Schimek |first2=Georges |last2=Darido |first3=Donald |last3=Schneck |date=September 2005 |publisher=Federal Transit Administration}}</ref>{{rp|1.2}} On July 20, 2002, new Silver Line-branded CNG buses began operation - the first low-floor buses to operate in Boston - and the 20 stops were reduced to 11.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|1.2, 4.11}} (In November 2002, a twelfth stop at {{bts|Worcester Square}} was restored.)<ref name=2005report />{{rp|2.5}} The {{convert|40|ft|adj=on}} were replaced by {{convert|60|ft|adj=on}} buses in August 2003, and service frequency was again increased.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|1.2}} On January 31, 2005, the route was the first MBTA bus route to receive new [[automated fare collection]] equipment.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|2.9}} By 2005, ridership was double that of route 49, but early decreases in travel time were cancelled out by longer dwell times.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|4.4, 5.1}} In February 2020, the MBTA agreed to change the name of Dudley Square station to Nubian Square, following the December 2019 renaming of the square itself.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/02/16/mbta-dudley-nubian-station-roxbury |title=Roxbury's Dudley Station To Be Renamed Nubian Station |last=Menard |first=Fausto |date=February 16, 2020 |website=[[WBUR-FM|WBUR]] |access-date=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Waterfront development===\n[[File:Outbound MBTA Silver Line buses at Courthouse station.jpg|thumb|right|A 40-foot Silver Line [[trolleybus]] at Courthouse station in 2005. These buses were briefly used until the dual-mode buses entered service.]]\n[[File:Silver Line service plan map, 2005.jpg|thumb|right|Silver Line service plans as of 2005, showing the SL3 (discontinued in 2009) and the original SL4 and Phase III (never implemented)]]\nFor most of the 20th century, the [[Seaport District]] was an industrial area occupied by [[Track 61 (Boston)|rail yards]] and wharves; the [[South Boston Army Base]] and [[South Boston Naval Annex]] were served by short bus routes that connected with the [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red Line]] at {{bts|South Station}}.<ref>{{cite map |title-link=:commons:File:1965 MBTA system map.png |year=1965 |first=Richard F. |last=Lufkin |title=System Route Map |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |via=Wikimedia Commons}}</ref> After the military bases closed in 1974 and the rail yards were no longer needed, the Seaport was designated for commercial development, with accompanying need for expanded transit.<ref name=feis />{{rp|1.1}} The MBTA conducted a feasibility study in 1987 and released a Draft [[Environmental Impact Report]] (DEIR) in 1989.<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/southbostonpiers00mass/ |chapter=Public scoping session |title=South Boston Piers/Fort Coint Channel Area Transportation Alternatives Environmental Impact Report |date=December 10, 1987 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |via=Internet Archive}}</ref><ref name=2007report />{{rp|23}} The DEIR selected an underground \"transitway\" over alternatives including a surface light rail line, an elevated [[people mover]], a commuter rail shuttle, and a relocation of the Red Line. The transitway was to use [[trolleybus]]es or [[dual-mode bus]]es, rather than the [[light rail]] and people mover possibilities considered; it would connect with the Red Line at South Station, the [[Orange Line (MBTA)|Orange Line]] at {{bts|Chinatown}}, and the [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]] at {{bts|Boylston}}. Costs could be reduced by combining its construction with the upcoming [[Central Artery/Tunnel Project]] (\"Big Dig\"). Service from the transitway could be extended to serve [[Logan International Airport]], to form part of [[Urban Ring (MBTA)|a proposed circumferential transit line]], and to connect with the planned Washington Street service.<ref name=feis>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/southbostonpiers00usde |title=South Boston Piers / Fort Point Channel transit project, Boston, Massachusetts: Final Environmental Impact Statement / Final Environmental Impact Report |date=December 1993 |publisher=Federal Transit Administration and Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |via=Internet Archive}}</ref>{{rp|iii}}\n\nThe South Boston Piers Transitway alignment was refined by the Draft Environmental Impact Statement (DEIR) in 1992.<ref name=feis />{{rp|V}} The Final Environmental Impact Statement/Final Environmental Impact Report (FEIS/FEIR) was approved in December 1993.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|24}} The South Station-Seaport segment was to open in 2000, with the Boylston segment opening in 2006.<ref name=feis />{{rp|2.81}} The stations at {{bts|World Trade Center}}, {{bts|Courthouse}}, South Station, Chinatown, and Boylston would each have [[island platform]]s, and the tunnel could be later converted to light rail as a Green Line branch if needed.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Nhw3AQAAMAAJ |chapter=Design Drawings Appendix |title=South Boston Piers / Fort Point Channel transit project, Boston, Massachusetts: Final Environmental Impact Statement / Final Environmental Impact Report |date=December 1993 |publisher=Federal Transit Administration and Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Phw3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA14 |chapter=Response to Comments Appendix |title=South Boston Piers / Fort Point Channel transit project, Boston, Massachusetts: Final Environmental Impact Statement / Final Environmental Impact Report |date=December 1993 |publisher=Federal Transit Administration and Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |page=14 |via=Google Books}}</ref> Daily ridership was expected to be between 24,200 and 37,200 for the first phase, and between 34,800 and 69,800 for the full build, depending on the rate of commercial development.<ref name=feis />{{rp|4.26}} In November 1994, the [[Federal Transit Administration]] (FTA) agreed to fund $331 million (80%) of the $413 million first phase, which was to be completed in December 2000.<ref name=gao2000>{{cite report |url=https://www.gao.gov/assets/100/90177.pdf |title=Mass Transit: Review of the South Boston Piers Transitway Finance Plan |publisher=General Accounting Office |date=November 9, 2000}}</ref>{{rp|1}} The environmental approval process was completed in April 1995.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|24}}\n\nIn 1997, with construction on the transitway already under way, [[Massport]] cancelled a planned people mover at Logan Airport in favor of dual-mode buses operating from the transitway and through the newly-opened [[Ted Williams Tunnel]].<ref name=2007report />{{rp|24\u201325}}<ref name=phase3 />{{rp|2.1}} (Such use of the third harbor tunnel to run express bus service to the airport had been proposed as early as 1968.)<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/studyofimprovedh00mass/page/n97 |title=A study of improved high speed public transportation between Logan International Airport and downtown Boston |page=98 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority and Massachusetts Port Authority |date=December 18, 1968 |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> A connector road was to extend the transitway from D Street to Haul Road. These changes were approved in February 1998.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|25}} In May 1999, the MBTA indicated plans to through-route the transitway with the planned Washington Street service as the \"Silver Line\", with the Washington Street service as Phase I, the initial Transitway build as Phase II, and the Boylston extension as [[#Phase III plans|Phase III]].<ref name=2007report />{{rp|25}}\n\nInitial construction of the Transitway was divided into four main sections: South Station and turnaround loop plus {{convert|1550|feet}} of tunnel ($96 million), Russia Wharf and Fort Point Channel tunnel ($128 million), Courthouse station plus {{convert|1450|feet}} of tunnel ($110 million), and World Trade Center station plus {{convert|1200|feet}} of tunnel ($43 million).<ref name=2007report />{{rp|15}} The Russia Wharf section, using the [[New Austrian tunnelling method]], was the most technically complex; [[ground freezing]] was required to support the historic [[Russia Wharf Buildings]]. It also included an [[immersed tube]] under the Fort Point Channel.<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JCJnZLCuOUEC&pg=PA265 |chapter=Jet grout bottom seal for cut and cover tunnel |first=Thomas M. |last=Hurley |title=North American Tunneling 2004: Proceedings of the North American Tunneling Conference 2004 |editor=Levent Ozdemir |year=2004 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=9781439833759 |pages=265\u2013270 |via=Google Books}}</ref> The discovery of a massive boulder under the Channel delayed the project by a year.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|15}} By late 2000, the project was three years behind schedule and almost $200 million over budget; the MBTA diverted $150 million of other federal grants and $50 million of contingency funds to cover the costs.<ref name=gao2000 />{{rp|4}} The Transitway was ultimately completed in 2004, with a final cost to the MBTA of $624 million. (That figure includes the higher-than-expected cost of dual-mode buses, and part of the cost of the Southampton maintenance facility, but subtracts reimbursements from other projects.)<ref name=2007report />{{rp|16}}<ref name=gao2000 />{{rp|5}} Although some projects like the [[John Joseph Moakley United States Courthouse|new federal courthouse]] and the [[Boston Convention and Exhibition Center|new convention center]] had been built, commercial development had lagged early plans; the MBTA adjusted its 2006 daily ridership projections from 45,000 to 14,000 shortly before opening.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.boston.com/news/local/articles/2004/11/22/bus_tunnel_to_open_but_waterfront_boom_lags?pg=full |title=Bus tunnel to open, but waterfront boom lags |date=November 22, 2004 |first=Anthony |last=Flint |newspaper=Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nThe Transitway opened on December 17, 2004, with the Waterfront shuttle route between South Station and Silver Line operated by a mix of new dual-mode buses and {{convert|40|ft|adj=on}} trolleybuses borrowed from the [[Trolleybuses in Greater Boston|Harvard-based routes]].<ref name=\"netransit\">{{NETransit}}</ref><ref name=2007report />{{rp|26}} It was only the third \"urban trolleybus subway\" (tunnel with stations) in the world, after the [[Harvard station|Harvard Bus Tunnel]] and the [[Downtown Seattle Transit Tunnel]] (in which trolleybus service ended in 2005).<ref name=tm2006>{{cite magazine |magazine=Trolleybus Magazine |title=Trolleynews |page=70 |editor-first=Peter |editor-last=Haseldine |volume=42 |issue=267 |date=May\u2013June 2006|publisher=National Trolleybus Association|location=UK|issn=0266-7452}}</ref> On December 31, 2004, service began on routes SL2 to the [[Boston Marine Industrial Park]] (BMIP) and route SL3 to {{bts|City Point}}. Two days later, a Sunday-only Silver Line Way-Logan Airport shuttle service called \"Silver Line Connector\" began operation to meet a legal commitment to begin airport service that month.<ref name=netransit /> The existing surface routes in the Seaport were discontinued or rerouted in January.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|5\u20137}} Due to a lack of available dual-mode buses, CNG shuttles operated on the surface sections of the SL2 and SL3 routes from January 5 to March 14, 2005. On March 26, the two routes were combined on nights and weekends.<ref name=netransit /> On April 9, weekday SL3 service was extended from City Point to a loop on Farragut Road.<ref name=netransit />\n\nOn May 28, 2005, the two routes were combined at all times as the SL2/3. This freed up buses for SL1 service to Logan Airport, which began on June 1.<ref name=netransit /> As more buses entered service, the SL2 and SL3 were resplit into separate routes (except nights and weekends) on August 20, and the Farragut Road loop was cut due to noise complaints from residents.<ref name=2008serviceplan /> On October 15, City Point service was cut on nights and weekends.<ref name=netransit /> An SL4 route from South Station to [[Andrew (MBTA station)|Andrew station]] via the [[Boston Convention and Exhibition Center]] and D Street was planned to open in 2005, but was never implemented.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://archives.lib.state.ma.us/bitstream/handle/2452/37411/ocm10561343-2005-01.pdf |journal=TRANSreport |date=January 2005 |publisher=Boston Region Metropolitan Planning Organization |title=The Silver Line Waterfront Line Opens for Service |page=1 |accessdate=November 25, 2015}}</ref><ref name=netransit /> As enough dual-mode buses became available, the borrewed 40-foot trolleybuses were phased out; they were last used on February 12, 2006.<ref name=tm2006 /> By 2006, the Silver Line had doubled transit ridership to the Seaport, and increased transit ridership to Logan by 24%.<ref name=2007report>{{cite report |url=https://www.transit.dot.gov/sites/fta.dot.gov/files/FINALBOSTONBRTREPORT062507.pdf |title=Silver Line Waterfront Bus Rapid Transit (BRT): 2007 Evaluation |date=June 1, 2007 |first1=Paul |last1=Schimek |first2=Kari |last2=Watkins |first3=David |last3=Chase |first4=Karl |last4=Smith |first5=Stephen |last5=Gazillo |publisher=Federal Transit Administration}}</ref>{{rp|42, 44}} The SL3 service was never successful, as the parallel route {{MBTABus|7}} route had a more direct route, lower fares, and better downtown connections. By 2008, the SL3 averaged less than one passenger per trip on the segment not shared with the SL2.<ref name=2008serviceplan>{{cite report |url=http://www.mbta.com/uploadedFiles/About_the_T/T_Projects/T_Projects_List/ServicePlan08.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908100943/http://www.mbta.com/uploadedFiles/About_the_T/T_Projects/T_Projects_List/ServicePlan08.pdf |archivedate=September 8, 2008 |title=Preliminary 2008 Service Plan: Bus, Rapid Transit, and Boat Service Changes and Service Delivery Policy Modifications |page=45 |date=Fall 2008 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref> On March 20, 2009, SL3 service was cut, with SL2 service increased in its stead.<ref name=netransit /> In October 2009, the SL2 terminus was renamed \"Design Center\" with no changes in service.<ref name=netransit />\n\nUntil 2019, SL2 buses served the Design Center loop in two different patterns. Before noon, outbound buses proceeded around the whole loop, laid over at the Design Center stop, then proceeded inbound. After noon, outbound buses made a shorter western loop, laid over at Design Center, then proceeded inbound via the main loop.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cdn.mbta.com/sites/default/files/projects/betterbus/route-profiles/SL2.pdf |title=Route SL2: Design Center \u2013 South Station |work=Better Bus Project |date=December 2018 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref> On December 22, 2019, the route was changed so that buses proceeded around the whole loop before the layover at all times.)<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://mbta.com/news/2019-12-07/bus-schedule-changes-winter-2020 |title=Bus Schedule Changes for Winter 2020 |date=December 7, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref><ref name=netransit /> On March 15, 2020, afternoon service began laying over at 23 Dry Dock Avenue before making the loop.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://mbta.com/news/2020-02-29/bus-schedule-changes-spring-2020 |title=Bus Schedule Changes for Spring 2020 |date=February 29, 2020|publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref><ref name=netransit />\n\n{{Anchor|Phase III}}\n\n=== Phase III plans===\n[[File:Silver Line Phase III alternatives.svg|thumb|right|Silver Line Phase III alternatives, showing the original 4 alignments plus the Charles Street Modified (CSM) alignment. The preferred route at the time of the project's cancellation was the CSM alignment (pink) feeding into the core tunnel (green).]]\nThe Boylston extension, as planned in 1993, would have run west from South Station under Essex Street, Avenue de Lafayette, and Avery Street. The Chinatown platform would have been under Hayward Place east of Washington Street, and the Boylston platform under the existing Green Line station, with a turnaround loop under Boylston Street and the [[Central Burying Ground]].<ref name=phase3>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ho3AQAAMAAJ |title=Silver Line Phase III: Supplemental Draft Environmental Impact Statement / Supplemental Environmental Impact Report |publisher=Federal Transit Administration and Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=June 2005 |volume=1 |via=Google Books}}</ref>{{rp|2.5\u20136}} The 1999 decision to combine the Waterfront and Washington Street projects as the Silver Line resulted in the addition of a southern segment, likely using the same abandoned streetcar tunnel as had been proposed a decade before. A new underground station would have been built under Tremont Street, connecting to the existing {{bts|New England Medical Center}} (NEMC) station, with a portal to Washington Street just north of Oak Street.<ref name=phase3 />{{rp|2.5\u20137}} In April 2000, the MBTA adjusted the alignment to use Boylston Street instead of Avenue de Lafayette and Avery Street, with side platforms at the stations. The new alignment would conflict less with development, provide a straighter route, avoid the need for a pedestrian crossing and a lengthy pedestrian tunnel at Chinatown, and move the Boylston loop away from the Burying Ground.<ref name=phase3 />{{rp|2.8}}\n\nIn January 2002, the MBTA began seeking federal funding for 60% of the project cost. The [[Federal Transit Administration]] (FTA) approved the project for further planning than July.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|27}} The Boston Regional Metropolitan Planning Organization rated the project as \"high priority\" in its May 2003 Program for Mass Transportation, citing its high estimated ridership, low operating cost and service to environmental justice neighborhoods.<ref name=PMT3>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206131017/http://www.bostonmpo.org/bostonmpo/pmt-old/PMT-3.pdf |archivedate=February 6, 2012 |url=http://www.bostonmpo.org/bostonmpo/pmt-old/PMT-3.pdf |title=Chapter 5C: System Expansion |work=Program of Mass Transportation |date=May 2003 |publisher=Boston Regional Metropolitan Planning Organization |accessdate=May 6, 2013 |page=5C-6,8,10,12,16}}</ref> In 2003, the preferred portal location was moved slightly north to avoid the need to demolish the YMCA building, and the NEMC station was removed.<ref name=phase3 />{{rp|2.10\u201315}} A proposal to consolidate the Chinatown and Boylsyon stations was rejected due to steep grades required and lack of cost savings, and a proposal to eliminate the loop was rejected because of the need to short turn most buses at Boylston.<ref name=phase3 />{{rp|2.15\u201322}} Further changes in 2003-04 were caused by the need to add a second platform at Boylston due to high expected ridership, and to reduce impacts to the historic [[Boston Common]] from the loop. One alternative placed the station and loop under Tremont Street south of Boylston Street; the other enlarged them under the Common.<ref name=phase3 />{{rp|2.22\u201325}}\n\nContinued concerns about the Common, concerns from [[Bay Village, Boston|Bay Village]] residents about impacts to Eliot Norton Park, and desires to add Back Bay service resulted in further changes in 2004\u201305. The platforms at Boylston were to be aligned east\u2013west under Boylston Street west of Tremont Street, with the loop further to the west at Charles Street. New portal alignments were considered, including one on [[Columbus Avenue (Boston)|Columbus Avenue]] to the southwest.<ref name=phase3 />{{rp|2.23\u201328}} Capital cost was originally estimated at $768\u2013812 million depending on the portal location; completion was moved from 2010 to 2013.<ref name=phase3 />{{rp|3.38, 6.1}} Daily ridership for the completed Silver Line system was estimated to reach 160,000 by 2025.<ref name=phase3 />{{rp|3.33}} In August 2005, the MBTA put the Phase III project \"on hold\" in order to  build community consensus on a locally preferred routing.<ref name=3dphase>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060115180758/http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2005/08/18/mbta_puts_hold_on_3d_final_phase_of_its_silver_line/ |archivedate=January 15, 2006 |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2005/08/18/mbta_puts_hold_on_3d_final_phase_of_its_silver_line/ |newspaper=The Boston Globe |title=MBTA puts hold on 3d, final phase of its Silver Line |first=Mac |last=Daniel |date=August 18, 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2006, State Transportation Secretary John Cogliano proposed a $94 million plan that would eliminate most of the tunneling and cost of the original proposal while still connecting the two phases of the service.<ref name=essex /> Under Cogliano's plan, the Silver Line would run on the surface via Kneeland Street and Surface Road to a new tunnel portal on Essex Street near South Station. A fare-controlled shelter would be added at Downtown Crossing for routes still terminating there. The plan also included expansion of surface Silver Line service, with a new branch running from [[Copley Square]] into the Essex Street portal to provide a one-seat ride from the Back Bay area. The southern branch would be extended from Dudley to the [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red Line]] stations at {{bts|Mattapan}} via Blue Hill Avenue (replacing route {{MBTABus|28}}) and{{bts|Ashmont}} via Washington Street (replacing route {{MBTABus|23}})<ref name=essex>{{cite news |url=http://archive.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2006/02/10/new_silver_line_plan_offered_stirring_critics/?page=full |title=New Silver Line plan offered, stirring critics |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=February 10, 2006 |author=Daniel, Mac |accessdate=May 6, 2013}}</ref> The plan was popular with Bay Village residents who had been worried about the full-length tunnel, but attracted criticism because it would not substantially speed travel times to downtown.<ref name=essex />\n[[File:SouthStationSL4shelter.agr.jpg|thumb|Shelter at [[South Station]] for route SL4]]\nA revised tunnel plan was put forward in March 2006, with support from most transportation leaders including Cogliano. The plan involved a variation of the Charles Street tunnel alignment, with the portal moved southwest onto Tremont Street near Marginal Road.<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102104009/http://mbta.com/uploadedFiles/About_the_T/T_Projects/T_Projects_List/Silver%20Line%20-%20Four%20Alternative%20Alignments.pdf |title=Alternatives Studied |url=http://mbta.com/uploadedFiles/About_the_T/T_Projects/T_Projects_List/Silver%20Line%20-%20Four%20Alternative%20Alignments.pdf |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |author=URS / DMJM Harris |accessdate=May 6, 2013 |archivedate=January 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060615023507/boston.com/news/local/articles/2006/03/10/officials_endorse_silver_line_tunnel/ |archivedate=June 15, 2006 |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2006/03/10/officials_endorse_silver_line_tunnel |title=Officials endorse Silver Line tunnel |author=Daniel, Mac |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=March 10, 2010 |accessdate=April 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091229163124/http://www.mbta.com/uploadedFiles/About_the_T/T_Projects/T_Projects_List/Silver%20Line%20Phase%20III%20--%20Charles%20Modified%20Alignment.pdf |url=http://www.mbta.com/uploadedFiles/About_the_T/T_Projects/T_Projects_List/Silver%20Line%20Phase%20III%20--%20Charles%20Modified%20Alignment.pdf |title=Charles Street Modified (CSM) alignment |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |author=URS / DMJM Harris |accessdate=May 6, 2013 |archivedate=December 29, 2009}}</ref> This \"Charles Street Modified\" alignment remained the preferred alternative for the remainder of the project. Contra-flow dedicated bus lanes, already in place on Washington Street, were to be extended onto Marginal Road and Herald Street to allow buses to reach the portal from the surface section.<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102104056/http://mbta.com/uploadedFiles/documents/CSM_portal_graphic.pdf |url=http://mbta.com/uploadedFiles/documents/CSM_portal_graphic.pdf |title=Tremont Two-way Portal Contra Flow Alternative |work=Silver Line Phase III: Tunnel and System Wide Elements |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |author=URS / DMJM Harris |accessdate=May 6, 2013 |archivedate=January 2, 2010}}</ref> On December 12, 2006, the FTA approved the project to re-enter its funding process.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|27}} By mid-2008, environmental review and preliminary engineering were expected to be completed by the end of the year, with federal funding sought in 2010 and construction lasting from 2011 to a 2016 opening.<ref name=\"all_about\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/t_projects/?id=1072 |title=MBTA Transit Projects: Silver Line Phase 3 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206090354/http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/t_projects/?id=1072 |archivedate=December 6, 2008 |accessdate=June 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mysouthend.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=&sc2=news&sc3=&id=78529 |title=Silver Line Phase III moving forward |author=Kearnan, Scott |date=August 7, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714144532/http://www.mysouthend.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=&sc2=news&sc3=&id=78529 |archivedate=July 14, 2011 |newspaper=My South End}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the estimated price of the tunnel plan, dubbed the \"Little Dig\", had risen to $2.1 billion by May 2009.<ref name=littledig>{{cite news |url=http://archive.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2009/05/10/little_dig_in_danger/ |title=Little Dig in Danger |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=May 10, 2009 |accessdate=April 22, 2011}}</ref> The FTA assigned it a ''Medium Low'' overall rating, making it ineligible to move into the final design phase for federal New Starts funding. The Boston Region Metropolitan Planning Organization removed Phase III from the list of recommended projects in its long range plan because of funding limitations \u2013 a rapid turnaround from its \"high priority\" rating in 2003. Concluding that it could not successfully compete for more than one New Starts grant, MassDOT informed the FTA that it was no longer seeking New Starts money for Phase III. All New Starts funds available would instead be directed to the legally mandated [[Green Line Extension]] project. In a July 2010 report, the MBTA declared that Phase III was on indefinite hold and no further funds would be spent on the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://old.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/About_the_T/Environment/2010%20Annual%20Report.pdf |title=Annual Status Report |date=July 9, 2010 |author=Mohler, David J. |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |accessdate=May 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA partial solution that did not require a new tunnel opened on October 13, 2009, after expedited construction using [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|federal stimulus money]]. The new route, SL4, covered much of the same alignment as the proposed Phase III, with a dedicated bus lane on Essex Street and a South Station stop west of Atlantic Avenue. The existing Downtown Crossing-Dudley route was renamed SL5 at that time.<ref name=directconnect>{{cite press release |url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2009-10-13/patrick-murray-administration-mayor-menino-launch-silver-line-direct-connect |title=PATRICK-MURRAY ADMINISTRATION, MAYOR MENINO LAUNCH SILVER LINE DIRECT CONNECT SERVICE TO SOUTH STATION |date=October 13, 2009 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Extension to Chelsea|Chelsea|Silver Line Gateway}}\n\n===Extension to Chelsea===\n[[File:Chelsea Station.agr.jpg|thumb|left|Chelsea station in July 2018]]\nThe [[Urban Ring Project (MBTA)|Urban Ring Project]] was a planned circumferential surface BRT line. It would have shared the Silver Line berths at Dudley Square, and have had a surface stop outside World Trade Center station, but otherwise would have been separate from the Silver Line.<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708181035/https://www.commentmgr.com/projects/1169/docs/URnews0105c.pdf |archivedate=July 8, 2011 |url=https://www.commentmgr.com/projects/1169/docs/URnews0105c.pdf |title=Urban Ring Phase 2 FACT SHEET |date=January 2009}}</ref><ref name=urplans>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227011401/http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/theurbanring/downloads/Plan_Profile_Drawings.pdf |archivedate=February 27, 2017 |url=http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/theurbanring/downloads/Plan_Profile_Drawings.pdf |title=The Urban Ring Phase 2: Revised Draft Environmental Impact Report/Statement |publisher=Massachusetts Executive Office of Transportation |date=November 2008}}</ref> The project was cancelled in 2010 due to high cost, but planning for several smaller sections continued.<ref name=ctps2012 >{{cite web |url=https://www.ctps.org/data/calendar/pdfs/2012/10.31_SilverLine.pdf |title=Work Program for: MBTA Silver Line to Chelsea: Alternatives Analysis, Phase 2 |first=Karl H. |last=Quackenbush |date=November 1, 2012 |publisher=Central Transportation Planning Staff}}</ref> The [[Chelsea, Massachusetts|Chelsea]]-South Boston section was given high priority because Chelsea was densely populated yet underserved by transit.<ref name=ctps2012 /> MassDOT had also purchased the [[Grand Junction Railroad|Grand Junction Branch]] - including abandoned sections in Chelsea and East Boston - from [[CSX Transportation]] in 2009, meaning that a potential right-of-way (which the urban Ring had proposed to use) was available.<ref name=ctps2012 /> A state study in 2011 analyzed potential Chelsea services, including a Silver Line branch or improvements to the route {{MBTABus|112}} bus.<ref name=ctps2012 />\n\nIn 2013, MassDOT began public planning of the ''Silver Line Gateway''. In addition to serving Chelsea, the proposed line would provide [[Blue Line (MBTA)|Blue Line]] riders a direct connection to the Seaport and South Station. Three possible alignments were studied. All used the Transitway and the Ted Williams Tunnel to reach {{bts|Airport}} station, then the 2012-opened Coughlin Bypass Road to the [[Chelsea Street Bridge]]. The first alignment was to run entirely on a new busway on the Grand Junction right-of-way in Chelsea, with stops at {{bts|Eastern Avenue}}, {{bts|Box District}}, {{bts|Bellingham Square}} (the Chelsea commuter rail station), and [[Chelsea station (MBTA)|Mystic Mall]]. The second alignment option would have followed the Grand Junction to just short of the commuter rail station, then diverge onto surface roads to Bellingham Square, while the third alignment would have run entirely on surface streets, serving two stops on Central Avenue and four stops along a loop serving Chelsea station and the MGH Chelsea healthcare center.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/Portals/31/Docs/SL_Gateway_June_19_2013_English_Accessible.pdf |title=Silver Line Gateway Alternatives Analysis |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation |date=June 19, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105011820/http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/Portals/31/Docs/SL_Gateway_June_19_2013_English_Accessible.pdf |archivedate=November 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, the MBTA indicated that it would pursue the first alternative, with an estimated daily ridership of 8,700, despite potential issues with bridge clearances and rebuilding the commuter rail station.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/Portals/31/Docs/SLG_092413_English.pdf |title=Silver Line Gateway Alternatives Analysis: Public Meeting \u2013 September 18, 2013 |date=September 18, 2013 |author=Hamwey, Scott |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105012200/http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/Portals/31/Docs/SLG_092413_English.pdf |archivedate=November 5, 2013}}</ref> On October 30, 2013, MassDOT announced $82.5 million in state funding for the new Silver Line route to Chelsea, with completion expected in 2015. The announcement also included the relocation of the commuter rail station to {{bts|Chelsea}} (Mystic Mall) and a $3 million, {{convert|3/4|mile|adj=on}} multi-use path from Eastern Avenue to Washington Street.<ref name=stateannouncement>{{cite press release |url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2013-10-30/gov-patrick-announces-expansion-silver-line |title=Governor Patrick Announces MBTA Silver Line Expansion |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=October 30, 2013}}</ref> MassDOT awarded a $33.8 construction contract for the first phase of the project on September 17, 2014. That phase included the {{convert|1.3|mile|adj=on}}-long busway, the four Silver Line stations, replacement of the Washington Street bridge, and the Chelsea Greenway.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://blog.mass.gov/transportation/mbta/mbta-silver-line-to-chelsea-approved/ |title=MBTA Silver Line to Chelsea Approved |date=September 17, 2014 |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation}}</ref>\n\nSilver Line service to Chelsea (route SL3) began on April 21, 2018.<ref>{{Cite press release |url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2018-03-12/new-silver-line-3-chelsea-service-between-chelsea-and-south-station |title=New Silver Line 3-Chelsea Service between Chelsea and South Station |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> By October, daily ridership reached 6,200.<ref name=chelseaupdate /> The second phase of the project includes the relocated Chelsea commuter rail station plus [[transit signal priority]] upgrades for the SL3. Construction began in August 2019, with completion planned for late 2021.<ref name=chelsea-commuter>{{cite web |url=https://www.mbta.com/projects/chelsea-commuter-rail-station |title=Chelsea Commuter Rail Station |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |accessdate=September 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Future development}}\n\n===Proposed future corridors===\n[[File:Pleasant Street Branch.png|thumb|right|Southern branch of the Tremont Street Subway near the former Pleasant Street Portal. This tunnel was briefly considered for use in the Phase III tunnel and is the likely connecting route for a proposed conversion of the Washington Street section of the Silver Line to a branch of the Green Line.]]\nSeveral other Bus Rapid Transit and express bus projects have been proposed in Boston, many under the Silver Line banner. The first two phases of the 2010-cancelled [[Urban Ring Project (MBTA)|Urban Ring Project]] were to be BRT, with light or heavy rail for the final phase. The Urban Ring was considered a separate project, although it would have shared the SL1 route between Silver Line Way and Logan Airport.<ref name=PMT3 />\n\nA number of Silver Line expansion corridors were considered in the 2003 Program for Mass Transportation (PMT); most were given brief consideration but not acted upon. One, a BRT express overlay for the [[28 (MBTA bus)|route 28 bus]] (which runs from [[Ruggles station]] to [[Mattapan (MBTA station)|Mattapan]] via Dudley), was revived in 2006 as part of Phase III plans. In 2009, the state proposed to replace the 28 bus entirely with a BRT route called 28X, including the installation of dedicated bus lanes, bus signal priority, and on-platform fare collection.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eot.state.ma.us/downloads/direct_connect/BRT-Brochure.pdf |title=Mattapan Bus Rapid Transit and South Station Direct Connect Project |publisher=Massachusetts Executive Office of Transportation |date=May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110108004614/http://www.eot.state.ma.us/downloads/direct_connect/BRT-Brochure.pdf |archivedate=January 8, 2011}}</ref> However, the proposal was withdrawn in 2010 due to local opposition, both to the design of the route and because the plan had been made with consulting local officials.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/2011/08/31/28x-debacle-missed-opportunities/ |title=The MBTA's 28X Debacle, aka, Missed Opportunity |newspaper=Boston Magazine |date=August 31, 2011 |first=Steve |last=Poftak}}</ref> (In 2012, the Roxbury-Dorcester-Mattapan Transit Needs Study recommended the 28X bus to be implemented with no new infrastructure as an express bus adding additional trips to the corridor.)<ref name=RDM>{{cite web |url=http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/rdm/downloads/RDMReport_0912.pdf |title=Roxbury-Dorchester-Mattapan Transit Needs Study |date=September 2012 |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation}}</ref>\n\nSeveral other corridors were considered in the 2003 PMT. These included a Dudley-Ashmont route replacing the [[23 (MBTA bus)|route 23 bus]] (also revived in 2006 in Phase III planning, but not during the 28X proposal), as well as a new BRT tunnel to [[Kenmore station|Kenmore]] with surface branches to the [[Longwood Medical Area]] via [[Brookline Avenue]] and [[Allston, Massachusetts|Allston]] via [[Commonwealth Avenue (Boston)|Commonwealth Avenue]], the [[Mass Pike]], and Cambridge Street.<ref name=PMT3 /><ref name=PMT4 /> The City of Boston proposed an alternate western Silver Line branch using buses along the Mass Pike without a new tunnel, similar to existing [[List of MBTA bus routes#501-599|express buses]].<ref name=PMT4>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206131017/http://www.bostonmpo.org/bostonmpo/pmt-old/PMT-4.pdf |archivedate=February 6, 2012 |url=http://www.bostonmpo.org/bostonmpo/pmt-old/PMT-4.pdf |title=Chapter 5C: System Expansion |work=Program of Mass Transportation |date=January 2004 |publisher=Boston Regional Metropolitan Planning Organization |page=5C\u201342,76}}</ref>\n\nThe 2003 PMT included the possibility of converting the Washington Street section of the Silver Line to light rail (as had originally been promised) using the abandoned southern section of the [[Tremont Street subway|Tremont Street Subway]]. The project was estimated to cost $374 million; ridership was estimated to be 34,000 daily riders almost entirely diverted from the Silver Line service. The project was given low priority, with the Phase III tunnel recommended instead.<ref name=PMT4 /> In 2012, the Roxbury-Dorcester-Mattapan Transit Needs Study recommended the conversion to light rail as a long-term project, with the additional possibility of extending the line down Blue Hill Avenue to [[Mattapan station|Mattapan]] along the route 28 bus corridor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/files/documents/2018/03/02/RDMreport.pdf|title=Roxbury-Dorchester-Mattapan Transit Needs Study|date=September 2012|page=53 |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, state and local officials indicated plans to extend service from [[Chelsea station (MBTA)|Chelsea]] on two routes to [[Kendall Square]] and to [[North Station]], both via [[Sullivan Square station|Sullivan Square]]. The routes would primarily use dedicated busways and bus lanes, although they may not be part of the Silver Line brand.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/03/16/silver-line-route-extending-sullivan-square-north-station-and-kendall/4OMXe8E66YRjdULWNDjRWL/story.html |title=Silver Line-style bus could serve Sullivan Square, North Station and Kendall |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=March 16, 2019 |first=Adam |last=Vaccaro}}</ref> In February 2020, the cities of Everett and Somerville submitted an application for $425,000 in [[Gambling in Massachusetts|Massachusetts Gaming Commission]] funds to design the extension.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://massgaming.com/wp-content/uploads/City-of-Everett-Silver-Line-Extension-Planning-and-Design-2020-Transportation-Planning-Application.pdf |title=2020 Transportation Planning Grant Application |publisher=Massachusetts Gaming Commission |year=2020}}</ref>\n\n==Service==\n===Frequency and ridership===\n[[File:MBTA route SLW bus at Courthouse station, March 2017.JPG|thumb|right|The SLW was one of three MBTA Bus routes to show a net profit in a 2012 study]]\nThe Silver Line routes are among the most frequent MBTA bus routes. All routes (except for the SLW shuttle) run at least every 15 minutes during all service hours, except for late evening service on the SL4. At peak hours, combined frequency on the trunk sections is about 30 buses per hour (2 minute headways) in each direction in the Transitway, and 12-14 buses per hour (4-5 minute headways) on Washington Street.<ref name=busmap /><ref name=profiles /> The routes have high ridership (though lower than many [[MBTA key bus routes|key bus routes]]) and low costs per rider compared to other bus routes in the MBTA system. In 2012, three routes (SL1, SL5, SLW) were the only MBTA bus routes to show a profit; the median net cost (after fares) on all MBTA bus routes was $2.13 per passenger.<ref name=\"RPI2012\">{{cite web |url=http://mbta.com/uploadedfiles/Fares_and_Passes_v2/Route%20Performance%20Indicators%207-6%20Fixed.pdf |title=MBTA Route Performance Indicators |year=2012 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |author=Office of Transportation Planning staff |accessdate=May 7, 2013}}</ref> In 2019, combined weekday ridership on Silver Line routes was 39,000.<ref name=ridership />\n\nIn addition to the [[MBTA nomenclature|public route name]], the Silver Line and [[MBTA crosstown bus routes|crosstown routes]] have internal route numbers in the 700 series. The SL5 is designated 749 after the 49 bus it replaced, while the other routes have similar numbers.<ref name=bluebook>{{MBTA Bluebook 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Route\n!#\n!Rush hour headways<ref name=busmap />\n!Midday headways<ref name=busmap />\n!Weekend headways<ref name=busmap />\n!Weekday ridership (2018)<ref name=profiles>{{cite web |url=https://www.mbta.com/projects/better-bus-project/update/bus-route-profiles-now-available |title=Bus Route Profiles Now Available |date=December 10, 2018 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n|-\n|SL1\n|741\n|8\u201310 minutes\n|8 minutes\n|8\u201312 minutes\n|8,132\n|-\n|SL2\n|742\n|5 minutes\n|10 minutes\n|15 minutes\n|6,420\n|-\n|SL3\n|743\n|10\u201312 minutes\n|15 minutes\n|12\u201315 minutes\n|6,200<ref name=chelseaupdate />\n|-\n|SLW\n|746\n|10 minutes\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|(not available)\n|-\n|SL4\n|751\n|9 minutes\n|15 minutes\n|15 minutes\n|5,800\n|-\n|SL5\n|749\n|8 minutes\n|10 minutes\n|7\u20138 minutes\n|10,300\n|}\n\n===Criticism===\n====Mode choice====\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = This is not bus rapid transit. All they did was take a diesel bus, change the engine, paint it silver and run it down the street through traffic.\n |author = Roxbury activist Bob Terrell<ref name=localdiversity />\n |width = 300px\n |quoted=1\n}}\nWhen the Washington Street Elevated was replaced with the Southwest Corridor, MBTA promised \"equal or better\" surface transit on Washington Street to replace the Elevated.<ref name=essex /> Riders supported light rail; the decision to instead run buses was viewed as a broken promise and intentional disinvestment.<ref name=localdiversity /><ref name=ITDP /> The Silver Line is substantially slower than the Elevated, with travel time from Nubian Square to Downtown Boston increased from 8 minutes to 20 minutes.<ref name=essex /> The Washington Street corridor population is poorer and less educated than the Southwest Corridor, and has a larger Black population; advocates including state representative [[Gloria Fox]] have called the poor service on the Silver Line racial discrimination against Roxbury.<ref name=localdiversity /><ref>{{cite document |title=Moving forward equitably? : analyzing the impact of transportation changes on Boston's neighborhoods |pages=6\u20137 |last=Techagumthorn |first=Yanisa |publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology |year=2019|hdl = 1721.1/121751}}</ref> Because of the poor service and the perception that the bus service was an inferior substitute for the originally-planned light rail line, advocates nicknamed the Washington Street service as the \"Silver Lie\".<ref name=localdiversity>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpasAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA97 |title=Place-Based Education in the Global Age: Local Diversity |first1=David A. |last1=Gruenewald |first2=Gregory A. |last2=Smith |publisher=Routledge |year=2014 |isbn=9781317670636 |via=Google Books |chapter=A Bill, A \"Silver Lie,\" Budget Cuts, and Bioweapons: 2000\u20132005 |pages=95\u2013101}}</ref><ref name=anson>{{cite document |title=Visualizing urban accessibility metrics for incremental bus rapid transit projects |first=Anson Forest |last=Stewart |publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology |year=2014 |pages=92\u201394|hdl = 1721.1/92057}}</ref>\n\nTwo theoretical advantages of BRT compared to light rail are low cost and speedy implementation.<ref name=ITDP />{{rp|6}} However, Silver Line service did not begin Washington Street until 15 years after the Elevated came down; the first phase of the Transitway opened 15 years after the DEIR, and the second phase was never completed. The Transitway was built at \"enormous cost\"; it was the most expensive single BRT project in the world by a 2007 report.<ref name=ITDP /><ref>{{cite report |url=http://www.reconnectingamerica.org/assets/Uploads/bestpractice246.pdf |page=8 |title=Funding Bus Rapid Transit in the U.S. |first=Lisa |last=Callaghan |year=2007 |publisher=Transportation Research Board}}</ref> Like the [[Downtown Seattle Transit Tunnel]] (which was later converted to light rail), the Transitway had comparable construction cost to light rail, but a lower level of service.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKipDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA501 |page=501 |title=Transportation Planning Handbook |first=Michael D. |last=Meyer |year=2016 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=9781118762400 |via=Google Books}}</ref> At the time of its cancellation, Phase III was expected to cost $2.1 billion - more than three times that of the Transitway.<ref name=littledig /> Although transit ridership in the Seaport doubled after the introduction of the Silver Line, that growth is due partially to commercial development rather than the service quality.<ref name=ITDP /><ref name=anson />\n\n====BRT quality====\n[[File:Washington Street with bus lanes, August 2016.JPG|thumb|right|Red-painted bus lanes on an uncongested section of Washington Street]]\n[[File:Dual-mode bus in electric mode at top of Silver Line Waterfront tunnel ramp in Boston (2007).jpg|thumb|An SL1 bus waiting at the D Street light]]\nKey features of [[bus rapid transit]] include dedicated lanes, frequent service, off-vehicle fare collection, sheltered stations, and [[intelligent transportation systems]] (ITS) features such as [[transit signal priority]].<ref name=cham>{{cite document |title=Understanding bus service reliability : a practical framework using AVL/APC data |last=Cham |first=Laura Cecilia |year=2006 |publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|hdl = 1721.1/34381}}</ref>{{rp|99}} A 2011 study by the [[Institute for Transportation and Development Policy]] (ITDP) determined that the Silver Line was best classified as \"Not BRT\" because it lacked many of these [[BRT Standard]] features.<ref name=ITDP>{{cite web |last=Weinstock |first=Annie |title=Recapturing Global Leadership in Bus Rapid Transit |url=http://www.itdp.org/documents/20110526ITDP_USBRT_Report-HR.pdf |publisher=Institute for Transportation and Development Policy |date=May 2011 |display-authors=etal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503065258/http://www.itdp.org/documents/20110526ITDP_USBRT_Report-HR.pdf |archivedate=May 3, 2012 |pages=45\u201346}}</ref>\n\nOff-board fare collection is only present at the three underground stops.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|12}}  A significant portion of delays on the surface sections are caused by long [[dwell time (transportation)|dwell time]]s, as passengers only board through the front door to pay at the single farebox. On June 6, 2012, [[Massport]] began funding a three-month pilot of free fares from the five Logan Airport stops as an effort to decrease traffic congestion at the airport terminals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2012/06/05/mbta-give-free-rides-from-airport/4ELdEe4yNLcqakFkZt5LmJ/story.html |title=MBTA to give free rides from airport |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=June 5, 2012 |first=Eric |last=Moskowitz}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.massport.com/massport/media/newsroom/logan-passengers-ride-fare-free-on-the-silver-line/ |title=Pilot Program Offers Logan Passengers Free Silver Line Ride from Logan Airport to South Station |date=June 5, 2012 |publisher=Massachusetts Port Authority}}</ref> Within the first month, average dwell time dropped by 20 seconds per stop.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.massport.com/massport/media/newsroom/free-silver-line-from-logan-airport-to-continue/ |title=Free Silver Line Rides from Logan to Continue Through September Program Shaves Almost Two Minutes off 10 minute Route; More Ridership Data Needed |date=July 19, 2012 |publisher=Massachusetts Port Authority}}</ref> Massport later extended the pilot until January 2013, then made free fares from Logan permanent.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.massport.com/massport/media/newsroom/free-silver-line-service-continues-through-new-year/ |title=Massport Holds the Line on Boston Logan Rates and Charges; Free Silver Line Service to Continue through New Year |date=September 20, 2012 |publisher=Massachusetts Port Authority}}</ref><ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.massport.com/media/2279/2014_edr_web_version_file1.pdf |title=2014 Environmental Data Report |pages=5\u201326 |chapter=Ground Access to and from Logan Airport |date=September 2015 |publisher=Massachusetts Port Authority}}</ref><ref name=tariff />{{rp|31}} Stops on the Washington Street routes with more than fifteen passengers have an average dwell time over one minute, which affects both running time and reliability.<ref name=alldoorpilot /> A two-week pilot program in 2017 tested all-door boarding on these routes, with free fares funded by a nonprofit. The pilot halved dwell times at busy stops, reduced overall average dwell time from 24 to 19 seconds, and increased reliability.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vaccaro |first1=Adam |title=All-door boarding made Silver Line buses move a little quicker |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/10/07/all-door-boarding-made-silver-line-buses-move-little-quicker/tZp7E2VY6MGsWbfKv3Ku8I/story.html |accessdate=February 7, 2018 |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=October 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=alldoorpilot>{{cite web |url=https://www.mbtabackontrack.com/blog/74-all-door-boarding-pilot-on-the-silver-line |title=ALL-DOOR BOARDING PILOT ON THE SILVER LINE |date=October 10, 2017 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |work=Data Blog}}</ref> All-door boarding will be permanently implemented on all routes in the early 2020s as part of the [[AFC 2.0]] fare system.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mass.gov/files/documents/2019/05/06/dot_glx_AFC_2-0_overview_20190402.pdf |title=AFC 2.0 Next generation MBTA fare system |date=April 2, 2019 |first=David |last=Sikorski |page=4 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n\nThe Washington Street routes have dedicated bus lanes between {{bts|Herald Street}} and {{bts|Melnea Cass Boulevard}}, as well as on Essex Street.<ref name=directconnect /><ref name=2005report />{{rp|2.1}} However, these lanes are not physically separated from general traffic lanes and are designated as right-turn lanes at many intersections.<ref name=anson /><ref name=nacto /> A lack of loading zones causes many vehicles to double-park in the bus lanes, and violations of the exclusive lanes are rarely enforced.<ref name=ITDP /><ref name=nacto>{{cite report |url=https://nacto.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/brt_report_panero.pdf |title=Peer-to-Peer Information Exchange on Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) and Bus Priority Best Practices |pages=41\u201344 |first=Marta |last=Panero |display-authors=et al |date=May 2012 |publisher=Federal Transit Administration |chapter=Appendix A: New York Workshop Summary}}</ref> In the most congested parts of the corridor - Nubian Square and Downtown Crossing - no dedicated lanes are present.<ref name=anson /> Transit signal priority (TSP) was only planned for four locations on Washington Street. Due to conflicts between the MBTA, the contractors, and the city, the TSP equipment was not activated until 2006.<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.abettercity.org/docs/Surface%20Transportation%20Optimization%20and%20Bus%20Priority%20Measures%20Final.pdf |title=Surface Transportation Optimization and Bus Priority Measures: The City of Boston Context |page=23 |date=March 2013 |publisher=A Better City}}</ref><ref name=2005report />{{rp|2.10}} Due to the lack of BRT elements, running times on the corridor show significant variability. Peak-hour times were as much as 1.7 times that of uncontested periods in 2006, indicating that the limited BRT elements on Washington Street were ineffective at actually speeding travel during congested periods.<ref name=anson /> Headway reliability is poor, largely due to operators failing to depart Dudley Square on time.<ref name=cham />{{rp|136}} Additional enforced downtown bus lanes, plus traffic restrictions on Temple Place and new loading zones in Chinatown, were added by the city in October and November 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boston.gov/departments/transportation/silver-line-improvements-downtown |title=SILVER LINE IMPROVEMENTS: DOWNTOWN |publisher=City of Boston Transportation Department}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the Transitway is a dedicated bus tunnel without interference from automobile traffic, Waterfront service is no faster than the on-street buses it replaced.<ref name=ITDP /> The tunnel was built for a maximum speed of {{convert|25|mph}}; the narrow lanes without [[guided bus]]es limit actual speeds to {{convert|15|mph}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://commonwealthmagazine.org/transportation/forget-gondolas-turn-silver-line-green/ |title=Forget gondolas, turn Silver Line Green |first=Ari |last1=Ofsevit |first2=Ethan |last2=Kensky |date=March 10, 2018 |newspaper=Commonwealth Magazine}}</ref><ref name=2007report />{{rp|31}} Water leakage and poor drainage has damaged the concrete floor of the tunnel, leading to \"poor ride quality\".<ref name=stateofthesystem /> The switch between electric and diesel power at Silver Line Way also represents a \"significant delay\".<ref name=ITDP /> Because the original Transitway design ended at D Street, buses must cross the street at a traffic light. A 2003 study indicated extending the Transitway tunnel under D Street (\"T under D\") for [[grade separation]] was feasible, with a cost around $75 million.<ref>{{cite report |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mhs3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA9-IA99 |title=MBTA Silver Line Under D Street Feasibility Study |date=January 31, 2003 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |author=HDR |via=Google Books}}</ref> The light has attracted criticism from riders due to the delays it causes. A 2013 study found a median delay of 1.5 minutes per round trip at the light.<ref name=anson /><ref name=cao />{{rp|136}} In early 2016, the Boston Transportation Department modified the traffic light to use a fixed cycle, rather than relying on the detection of buses (only done during part of the cycle) to give a green light for the Transitway. However, the BTD's modifications did not modify the unusually-long 100-second cycle length nor actively prioritize buses, leading to criticism from transportation planners that the solution was inadequate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2016/02/20/what-going-with-silver-line-traffic-signal-street/EGyrgj2gV5Y6Cy3yQUyIOM/story.html |title=What's going on with the Silver Line traffic signal on D Street? |first=Nicole |last=Dungca |date=February 20, 2016 |newspaper=Boston Globe |accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> Proposed [[air rights]] development over the station is required not to preclude later grade separation of D Street.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.massport.com/rfpattachments/770cd19a-83ef-4341-b141-2bbf3664a505/01%20-%20Parcel%20H%20RFP%2006-27-2019.pdf |title=Request for Proposals For the PARCEL H DEVELOPMENT PROJECT |nopp=yes |page=Figure 12 |publisher=Massachusetts Port Authority |date=June 27, 2019}}</ref> A gate and movable bollard near the light, which are used to prevent private vehicles from entering the Transitway, also cause delays to buses.<ref name=cao>{{cite document |title=Improving public transportation to Boston Logan International Airport |last1=Cao |first1=Siyuan |last2=O'Connor |first2=Andrew |last3=Were |first3=Brenda |year=2013 |publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|hdl = 1721.1/82806}}</ref>{{rp|141}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2007-04-16/high-tech-keep-out |title=A High-tech Keep Out |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=April 14, 2007 |first=Megan |last=Tench |via=Massachusetts Institute of Technology}}</ref>\n\nAlthough stop spacing varies widely between BRT systems, distances from {{convert|0.5|miles}} to {{convert|1.0|miles}} are typically recommended.<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.apta.com/wp-content/uploads/Standards_Documents/APTA-BTS-BRT-RP-004-10.pdf |title=Bus Rapid Transit Service Design  |pages=11\u201312 |publisher=American Public Transportation Association |date=October 2010 |first1=Dave |last1=Roberts |display-authors=et al}}</ref> Even after dropping half the stops, the Washington Street corridor averages only {{convert|0.25|miles}} between stops, with several stop spacings as low as {{convert|0.10|miles}}.<ref name=cham />{{rp|102}}<ref name=2005report />{{rp|2.5}} The Washington Street stops were built with open canopies; protected shelters were not added until 2010.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|5.8}}<ref>{{cite press release |title=MBTA Silver Line Upgrades Coming |url=https://blog.mass.gov/transportation/mbta/mbta-silver-line-upgrades-coming/ |date=November 3, 2010 |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation}}</ref> A small traditional glass shelter is available at Temple Place; Boylston, Chinatown, and Tufts Medical Center have no shelters at all.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|3.2}} Silver Line Way and the SL2 surface stops have glass shelters or none at all; the SL3 surface stops have canopies without shelters.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|10}}\n\n{{anchor|ramp}}\n\n====Indirect routing====\n[[File:State Police ramp near Ted Williams Tunnel, June 2017.JPG|thumb|right|The disputed ramp in 2017]]\nBecause the Transitway was not originally designed for service to Logan Airport or Chelsea, it does not have a direct connection to the [[Ted Williams Tunnel]]. Outbound SL1 and SL3 buses must travel {{convert|0.5|miles}} west on Haul Road from Silver Line to access an eastbound ramp west of B Street, then travel east on a frequently-congested section of I-90. Inbound buses must exit I-90 at B Street and travel {{convert|0.3|miles}} east on Congress Street to reach Silver Line Way.<ref name=busmap /> An eastbound entrance ramp near Silver Line Way, normally restricted for use by [[Massachusetts State Police]] and [[MassDOT]] maintenance vehicles from an adjacent operations center, can shorten the outbound routing by about {{convert|0.7|miles}}. MassDOT claims the ramp was not designed for buses, though Big Dig planner [[Fred Salvucci]] has claimed it was.<ref name=couldget>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/07/31/silver-line-commutes-could-get-quicker-with-opening-small-highway-ramp/lCVZH3TDH77k1KvRZ9vhbO/story.html |title=Silver Line commutes could get quicker, with the opening of a small highway on-ramp |first=Adam |last=Vaccaro |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=July 31, 2018}}</ref> Outbound buses were temporarily allowed to use the ramp in 2006 after the [[Big Dig ceiling collapse]], when there was no regular eastbound traffic through the tunnel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/editorials/articles/2006/07/19/mbta_to_the_rescue/ |title=MBTA to the Rescue |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=July 19, 2006}}</ref><ref name=2007report />{{rp|14}} The Urban Ring was also proposed to use the ramp.<ref name=urplans /> A 2010 study indicated that the ramp was safe to used for the Silver Line.<ref name=cao />{{rp|163}}\n\nTransit advocates have since pushed to allow use of the ramp by Silver Line buses (\"Free the ramp\"), though MassDOT claims the ramp is not safe to use when highway traffic is freely flowing.<ref name=rampresults /> The MBTA hired a consultant in 2018 to study potential use of the ramp.<ref name=couldget /> In May 2019, MassDOT agreed to a limited test of ramp use, though advocates criticized MassDOT for limiting the test to only the evening peak hour, and only when highway speeds did not exceed {{convert|30|mph}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2019/05/21/silver-line-ramp |title=The MBTA is freeing the most controversial ramp in Boston. Sort of. |first=Nik| last=DeCosta-Klipa |date=May 21, 2019 |newspaper=Boston Globe}}</ref> The three-day test in August 2019 resulting in average time savings of 3\u20138 minutes per bus, with significantly larger time savings at the most congested times. After these results, MassDOT agreed to make modifications to the ramp entrance to eventually allow use of the ramp whenever traffic speeds are below 30&nbsp;mph.<ref name=rampresults>{{cite web |url=https://www.mass.gov/files/documents/2019/09/17/dot_Silver%20Line%20_EmergencyAccess_091619.pdf |title=South Boston Waterfront \u2013 Emergency Access Ramp: Silver Line |date=September 16, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation}}</ref>\n\n====Other issues====\nThe SL3 route is subject to frequent delays due to the opening of the [[Chelsea Street Bridge]] \u2013 as many as ten times per day \u2013 for ships serving the upstream oil terminals. Each bridge opening causes a delay of up to 20 minutes, and the only alternate route involves a lengthy detour on [[Massachusetts Route 1A|Route 1A]]. Federal regulations give priority to marine traffic.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/06/29/new-chelsea-silver-line-hits-bridge-delays/JEmI2Fzu1DCdcn0G0R7roJ/story.html |title=New Chelsea Silver Line hits bridge delays |first=Adam |last=Vaccaro |date=June 29, 2018 |newspaper=Boston Globe}}</ref> In December 2018, MassDOT officials sought to create a six-month pilot program to reduce peak-hour openings of the bridge, as well as the nearby [[Andrew P. McArdle Memorial Bridge|Meridian Street Bridge]] used by the busy {{MBTABus|116}} and {{MBTABus|117}} bus routes.<ref name=chelseaupdate>{{cite web |url=https://cdn.mbta.com/sites/default/files/fmcb-meeting-docs/2018/december/2018-12-17-fmcb-chelsea-task-force-update-original-accessible.pdf |title=Chelsea Update |date=December 17, 2018 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://chelsearecord.com/2018/12/22/mbta-massport-seek-pilot-for-chelsea-street-bridge-restrictions/ |title=MBTA, MassPort Seek Pilot for Chelsea Street Bridge Restrictions |newspaper=Chelsea Record |date=December 22, 2018 |first=Seth |last=Daniel}}</ref>\n\nThe CNG buses bought for the Washington Street service caused disruptive 35&nbsp;Hz vibrations in nearby residential buildings.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://trid.trb.org/view/813733 |title=Low-Frequency Noise Effects in Residential Buildings Along a Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) Route |journal=Noise-Con 04: The 2004 National Conference on Noise Control Engineering |year=2004 |last1=Towers |first1=David A. |last2=Ross |first2=Jason C. |last3=McDowell |first3=Jim}}</ref> It took a year to retrofit the fleet with new mufflers; during that time, older buses which did not have that problem were used at night.<ref name=2005report />{{rp|3.5}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Attached KML}}\n*[http://www.mbta.com/schedules/bus MBTA - Bus]\n\n{{MBTA}}\n{{Massport}}\n{{USBRT}}\n\n[[Category:Silver Line (MBTA)|*]]\n[[Category:Bus rapid transit in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Trolleybus transport in the United States]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Boston bus line}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox Bus transit\n| name            = MBTA Silver Line\n| image           = MBTA route SLW bus approaching World Trade Center station, March 2017.JPG\n| image_size      = 320px\n| image_caption   = A Silver Line bus approaching World Trade Center station\n| parent          = [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]\n| founded         = July 20, 2002 (Washington Street)<br>December 17, 2004 (Waterfront)\n| locale          = [[Boston]] and [[Chelsea, Massachusetts|Chelsea]], [[Massachusetts]]\n| service_type    = [[Bus rapid transit]] (disputed)\n| routes          = 6\n| stops           = 14 (Washington Street)<br />21 (Waterfront)\n| hubs            = {{bts|South Station Under}}, {{bts|Dudley Square}}\n| fleet           = 24 (Washington Street)<br />32 (Waterfront)\n| ridership       = 39,000 (Q2 2019)<ref name=ridership>{{cite web |url=https://cdn.mbta.com/sites/default/files/2019-10/2019-10-07-fmcb-M-ridership-quarterly-update-accessible.pdf |title=Quarterly Ridership Update |date=October 7, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |page=3 |first=Laura |last=Riegel}}</ref>\n| fuel_type       = [[Hybrid electric bus|Diesel hybrid]] (Washington Street)<br />Dual-mode diesel/[[trolleybus]] (Waterfront)\n| website         = [http://www.mbta.com/schedules/bus MBTA - Bus]\n}}\n\nThe '''Silver Line''' is a system of bus routes in [[Boston]] and [[Chelsea, Massachusetts]] operated by the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] (MBTA). It is operated as part of the [[MBTA Bus]] system, but branded as [[bus rapid transit]] (BRT) as part of the [[MBTA subway]] system. Six routes are operated as part of two disconnected corridors. {{As of|2019}}, weekday ridership on the Silver Line was 39,000.\n\nThe four Waterfront routes operate out of an underground terminal at {{bts|South Station Under}} and run through the South Boston Piers Transitway - a dedicated bus tunnel through the [[Seaport District]] with stations at {{bts|Courthouse}} and {{bts|World Trade Center}} . At {{bts|Silver Line Way}}, they fan out on the surface: the SL1 to [[Logan International Airport]], the SL2 to [[Boston Marine Industrial Park|Design Center]], and the SL3 to {{bts|Chelsea}} via [[East Boston]]. (An additional [[short turn]] route, SLW, runs only at peak hours between South Station and Silver Line Way.) The SL1 and SL3 operate in [[mixed traffic]] through the [[Ted Williams Tunnel]]; the SL3 uses a limited-access [[haul road]] in East Boston and a dedicated busway in Chelsea for part of its route. The SL2 operates in mixed traffic in the Seaport. The Waterfront routes use [[articulated buses|articulated]] [[dual-mode bus]]es that operate as electric [[trolleybus]]es in the Transitway and conventional diesel buses on the surface. Battery electric buses and a diesel hybrid bus with extended battery range are being tested; one of the types may ultimately replace the dual-mode buses.\n\nTwo routes operate on [[Washington Street (Boston)|Washington Street]] between [[Dudley Square station]] (at [[Nubian Square]] in [[Roxbury (Boston)|Roxbury]]) and [[Downtown Boston]]. The SL5 terminates at {{bts|Downtown Crossing}} and the SL4 on the surface at {{bts|South Station Under}}. The two routes operate mostly in [[bus lane|dedicated lanes]] on Washington Street and Essex Street, though sections in Downtown Boston and Nubian Square operate in mixed traffic. They use articulated diesel hybrid buses, which replaced [[compressed natural gas]] (CNG)-powered buses in 2016\u201317.\n\nThe Washington Street corridor was built to replace the [[Orange Line (MBTA)|Orange Line]] [[rapid transit]] line, which was moved from the [[Washington Street Elevated]] to the [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]] in 1987. Initial plans called for a [[light rail]] line operated as part of the [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]], but trolleybuses and later CNG buses were substituted. Service improvements to the route 49 bus began in 2001, and the Silver Line brand was introduced on July 20, 2002. The articulated CNG buses began operation in 2003. On October 13, 2009, the SL4 began service and the original route was designated SL5.\n\nPlanning began in 1987 for mass transit to serve the growing Seaport; a new transit tunnel called the South Boston Piers Transitway was chosen in 1989. It was to run from {{bts|Boylston}} to World Trade Center via {{bts|Chinatown}} and South Station, though the Boylston-South Station section was later deferred as a separate phase. After years of delays, service through the $624 million Transitway began on December 17, 2004. SL2 and SL3 service began on December 31, 2004, with the SL1 added on June 1, 2005. The original SL3 route to {{bts|City Point}} was discontinued on March 20, 2009. A separate SL3 route to Chelsea \u2014 originally planned as part of the cancelled [[Urban Ring Project (MBTA)|Urban Ring Project]] \u2013 began service on April 21, 2018.\n\nIn 1999, the MBTA designated the Washington Street and Transitway projects as the Silver Line, and planned for the Boylston tunnel extension to include a portal to Washington Street for through-running. The connecting tunnel from Washington Street to Boylston was designated as Phase III. After several design changes, by 2005 Phase III was expected to cost around $800 million; projected completion had been delayed from 2006 to 2010, then to 2013. The project was placed on hold in 2005; planning resumed in 2006 after the controversial portal was relocated. However, the project cost rose to $2.1 billion, and it was cancelled in 2010. Several other Silver Line extensions have been proposed, as has a conversion of the Washington Street corridor to light rail, but most have not been pursued.\n\nThe Silver Line has been the target of criticism by riders and transportation planners. The choice of buses rather than light rail on Washington Street was viewed by Roxbury residents as a deliberate slight, leading to the nickname of \"The Silver Lie.\" Much of the Silver Line is missing [[BRT Standard]] features such as enforced dedicated lanes, off-vehicle fare collection, sheltered stations, and [[transit signal priority]]; a 2011 report by the [[Institute for Transportation and Development Policy]] (ITDP) called the Silver Line \"Not BRT\". Because the Transitway was not originally designed for service to Logan Airport or Chelsea, it does not have a direct connection to the Ted Williams Tunnel. A normally-unused ramp would shorten the outbound routing by {{convert|0.7|miles}}; after years of controversy, [[MassDOT]] agreed in 2019 to allow limited use of the ramp.\n\n==Routes==\n{{anchor|Waterfront|SL1|SL2|SL3|SLW}}\n\n===Waterfront: SL1, SL2, SL3===\n{{MBTA Silver Line Waterfront}}\nThree Silver Line services operate from {{bts|South Station Under}} in a dedicated tunnel, the South Boston Piers Transitway, serving the underground {{bts|Courthouse}} and {{bts|World Trade Center}} stations in the [[Seaport District]] then splitting at the {{bts|Silver Line Way}} surface station.\n\n* '''SL1''' Logan Airport \u2013 South Station\n* '''SL2''' Design Center \u2013 South Station\n* '''SL3''' Chelsea \u2013 South Station\nDuring rush hours, additional [[short turn]]s (designated '''SLW''') are run between South Station and Silver Line Way to increase frequency in the Transitway.\n\nRoute SL2 runs on Northern Avenue, then on a one-way loop on Drydock Avenue and Black Falcon Avenue with multiple stops serving the Innovation and Design Building and the [[Port of Boston|Flynn Cruiseport Boston]]. Buses run clockwise around the loop, with a layover at Design Center Place in the morning and 23 Dry Dock Avenue in the afternoon. From Silver Line Way, route SL1 and SL3 buses loop backwards on Haul Road, then cross under [[Boston Harbor]] in the [[Ted Williams Tunnel]] to [[East Boston]]. Route SL1 loops around the [[Logan International Airport]] terminals, with stops at the arrivals level of each terminal (including two separate stops at lengthy Terminal B). Route SL3 serves {{bts|Airport}} station, follows the Coughlin Bypass Road, and crosses [[Chelsea Creek]] on the [[Chelsea Street Bridge]]. It then follows a dedicated busway to {{bts|Chelsea}}, with intermediate stops at {{bts|Eastern Avenue}}, {{bts|Box District}}, and {{bts|Bellingham Square}}.<ref name=busmap /><ref name=netransit /> The three Transitway stops are full rapid transit stations; the Chelsea busway stations have large concrete shelters, while most other surface stops have small shelters.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|10}}\n\nThe Waterfront routes have regular rapid transit fares.<ref name=tariff />{{rp|13}} Passengers enter through faregates at the three Transitway stations, and pay at the on-board farebox at all other stops.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|12}} Fares are free when boarding at the Logan Airport stops.<ref name=tariff />{{rp|31}} (Inbound SL3 fares in Chelsea are also temporarily free during the Tobin Bridge/Chelsea Curves Rehabilitation Project, which is expected to last until late 2020.)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mass.gov/info-details/about-the-tobin-bridgechelsea-curves-rehabilitation-project |title=About the Tobin Bridge/Chelsea Curves Rehabilitation Project |year=2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation}}</ref> Transfer is possible to the Red Line within fare control at South Station. Normal transfers to other routes are available with a CharlieCard; transfers to/from the [[Blue Line (MBTA)|Blue Line]] at Airport and the Washington Street routes are available with a CharlieTicket.<ref name=tariff />{{rp|27}}\n\nThe Waterfront routes primarily use {{convert|60|ft|adj=on}} [[articulated bus]]es with three doors, which provide greater capacity than standard {{convert|40|ft|adj=on}} transit buses. The [[dual-mode bus]]es operate as electric [[trolleybus]]es (similar to the [[Trolleybuses in Greater Boston|older Harvard-based trolleybus system]]) between South Station and Silver Line Way, and as conventional diesel buses on the surface branches.<ref name=roster /> The buses are low-floor and fully [[accessible]], with [[kneeling bus]] technology and a [[wheelchair ramp]] at the front door. The 32 dual-mode buses, built by [[Neoplan USA]], were delivered in 2004-05 and overhauled in 2014\u201318.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://bangordailynews.com/2018/0/28/news/aroostock/mma-completes-mbta-bus-contract-releases-more-than-50-employees-2/ |newspaper=Bangor Daily News |title=MMA completes MBTA bus contract, releases more than 50 employees |date=August 28, 2018 |first=Christopher |last=Bouchard}}</ref><ref name=2007report />{{rp|11}} Eight of the buses were funded by [[Massport]] and include luggage racks for airport passengers.<ref name=2007report />{{rp|11}} All Silver Line buses are maintained at Southampton Street Garage.<ref name=roster>{{cite web |url=http://www.transithistory.org/roster/ |title=The MBTA Vehicle Inventory Page |publisher=NETransit |accessdate=October 9, 2019}}</ref><ref name=2005report />{{rp|2.8}}\n\nThe existing dual-mode service pattern requires difficult-to-maintain dual-mode buses, and buses must make a time-consuming switch between modes at Silver Line Way.<ref name=ITDP /> Additionally, the [[overhead lines]] in the Transitway are difficult to maintain.<ref name=stateofthesystem>{{cite web |url=https://www.mbtafocus40.com/s/Bus-SoS-Report-Final-Accessible_121815.pdf |title=State of the System: Bus |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=December 2015 |pages=28, 39\u201340}}</ref> The MBTA has obtained several buses to test alternate options for Waterfront service. A single [[New Flyer]] [[hybrid electric bus|diesel hybrid bus]] with extended battery range - sufficient to run through the Transitway on battery power - was obtained as an option on a separate order; it entered testing in September 2018 and revenue service in December. If that bus is deemed successful, the MBTA could order up to 45 similar buses.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2018-09-26/first-extended-range-hybrid-bus-joins-mbta-silver-line-fleet |title=First Extended-range Hybrid Bus Joins MBTA Silver Line Fleet |date=September 26, 2018 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=MBTA Vehicle Inventory as of February 28, 2019 |first=Jonathan |last=Belcher |date=January\u2013February 2019 |magazine=Rollsign |volume=56 |issue=1/2 |page=19}}</ref> On July 31, 2019, the MBTA began using five New Flyer [[battery electric bus]]es on both Waterfront and Washington Street routes.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2019-07-31/first-zero-emission-battery-electric-buses-join-the-mbta-silver-line-fleet |title=First Zero-emission, Battery-electric Buses Join the MBTA Silver Line Fleet |date=July 31, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n{{anchor|Waterfront stops|Waterfront stop listing}}\n\n====Stop listing====\n[[File:Power changeover at Silver Line Way inbound, March 2016.JPG|thumb|right|The power changeover at Silver Line Way]]\n[[File:MBTA route SL2 bus on Black Falcon Avenue, June 2017.JPG|thumb|right|An SL2 bus on Black Falcon Avenue]]\n[[File:MBTA route SL3 bus at Airport Station, December 2018.JPG|thumb|right|An SL3 bus at Airport station]]\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Neighborhood\n!rowspan=2|Station\n!colspan=4|Services\n!rowspan=2|Service began\n!rowspan=2|Transfers and notes\n|-\n!SL1\n!SL2\n!SL3\n!SLW\n|-\n|[[Financial District (Boston)|Financial District]]\n|{{bts|South Station}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|rowspan=4|December 17, 2004\n|{{rint|us|Amtrak}} [[Amtrak]]: {{lnl|Amtrak|Acela Express}}, {{lnl|Amtrak|Lake Shore Limited}}, {{lnl|Amtrak|Northeast Regional}}<br>{{rint|Boston|rail}} [[MBTA Commuter Rail]]: [[Fairmount Line|Fairmount]], [[Framingham/Worcester Line|Framingham/Worcester]], [[Franklin Line|Franklin]], [[Greenbush Line|Greenbush]], [[Needham Line|Needham]], [[Old Colony Lines|Old Colony]], and [[Providence/Stoughton Line|Providence/Stoughton]] lines; [[CapeFLYER]] (seasonal)<br>{{rint|Boston|subway}} [[MBTA subway]]: [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red Line]], Silver Line ({{MBTABus|SL4}})<br>{{bus icon}} [[MBTA Bus]]: {{MBTABus|4|7|11}}<br>{{bus icon}} Intercity buses at [[South Station Bus Terminal]]\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Seaport District]]\n|{{bts|Courthouse}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|4}}\n|-\n|{{bts|World Trade Center}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|4}}\n|-\n|{{bts|Silver Line Way}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|Changeover point between [[Diesel engine|diesel]] and [[Overhead lines|overhead electric]] power (except SLW)\n|-\n|rowspan=6|[[East Boston]]\n|{{bts|Terminal A}}\n|align=center|\u25cf\n|\n|\n|\n|rowspan=5|June 1, 2005\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus {{MBTA