style=\"text-align:left;\" rowspan=\"2\"| ''Tennessee Sky''\n|-\n| 2016\n! scope=\"row\"| \"You're Not Alone\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/you-are-not-alone-single/id1142051015|title=You're Not Alone|publisher=iTunes Australia|accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[California Dreamin']]\" <small>(with [[Irwin Thomas|Jack Jones]])</small>\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n| \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''California Dreamin'''\n|-\n| 2019\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Nothing Can Stop Us Now\" <small>(with [[Regine Velasquez|Regine Velasquez-Alcasid]])</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/nothing-can-stop-us-now-single/1483030530|title= Nothing Can Stop Us Now - single with Regine Velasquez-Alcasid |website=Apple Music|accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n| \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| non-album single\n|-\n| 2020\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Heaven Knows\" <small>(with [[Morissette Amon]])</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/heaven-knows-single/1497690300|title= Heaven Knows - single with Morisette |website=Apple Music|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n| \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| non-album single\n|-\n| colspan=\"17\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:8pt;\"| \"\u2014\" denotes releases that did not chart or were not released.\n|}\n\n===Other singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of singles as featured artist\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:19em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref name=aus/>\n|-\n| 1988\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[You're Not Alone (Australian Olympians song)|You're Not Alone]]\"<br><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(as Australian Olympians)</span>\n| 18\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award<ref name=\"ARIA Award History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-artist.php?letter=R&artist=Rick%20Price|title=History: Winners by Artist: Rick Price|work=[[ARIA Award]]s|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA)|accessdate=9 February 2011}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n| 1992\n| [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA Song of the Year]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/music-news-voting-opens-for-apra-song-of-the-year-20160118|title=Voting Opens For APRA Song of the Year|website=Noise11.com|date=16 January 2016|accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref>\n| \"[[Heaven Knows (Rick Price song)|Heaven Knows]]\"\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| Won  \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1993|1993]]\n| Breakthrough Artist \u2013 Single\n| rowspan=\"2\"| \"[[Not a Day Goes By (Rick Price song)|Not a Day Goes By]]\" \n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fdd;\"| Nominated\n|-\n| Best New Talent\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fdd;\"| Nominated\n|-\n| [[ARIA Award for Breakthrough Artist \u2013 Album|Breakthrough Artist \u2013 Album]]\n| ''[[Heaven Knows (Rick Price album)|Heaven Knows]]''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fdd;\"| Nominated\n|-\n| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1994|1994]]\n| [[ARIA Award for Best Adult Contemporary Album|Best Adult Contemporary Album]]\n| \"Where Is the Love?\"\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fdd;\"| Nominated\n|-\n| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1995|1995]]\n| [[ARIA Award for Best Male Artist|Best Male Artist]]\n| \"[[River of Love (Rick Price song)|River of Love]]\"\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fdd;\"| Nominated\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.rickprice.com}}\n*[http://www.sonymusic.com/artists/RickPrice/ Sony BMG listing]\n\n{{Rick Price}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Price, Rick}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:APRA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Australian guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brisbane]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the Move and Electric Light Orchestra bassist|Rick Price (bassist)|the American golfer|Rick Price (golfer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Rick Price\n| image            = Rick Price untitled (70 of 244) (9587355771) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = Rick Price singing into a microphone with a dark red background\n| caption          = Live performance in 2013\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Rick Allan Price\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=y|1961|7|6}}\n| birth_place      = [[Beaudesert, Queensland]], Australia\n| origin           = Australasian\n| death_date       = <!-- {{death date and age|df=y|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop rock]]\n* [[Rock music|rock]]\n* [[country music|country]]\n* [[folk rock]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Gospel music|gospel]]\n* [[Celtic music|Celtic]]\n* [[a cappella]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer-songwriter|record producer|multi-instrumentalist}}\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Vocals]]\n* [[guitar]]\n* [[piano]]\n* [[drums]]\n* [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n* [[harmonica]]\n* [[ukulele]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 1970\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Sony BMG]]\n* Clarice\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Union Beau]]|Keren Minshull|[[Margaret Urlich]]|[[Tina Arena]]|[[Tommy Emmanuel]]|[[Irwin Thomas|Jack Jones]]|[[Yothu Yindi]]|[[The Robertson Brothers]]|[[Anthony Snape]]|[[Mitch Grainger]]|[[Regine Velasquez-Alcasid]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|https://www.rickprice.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Rick Allan Price''' (born 6 July 1961) is an Australian singer, songwriter, multi-instrumentalist and record producer. His debut album, ''[[Heaven Knows (Rick Price album)|Heaven Knows]]'', was released in July 1992, which peaked at No.&nbsp;3 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]]. It provided two top&nbsp;ten singles, \"[[Not a Day Goes By (Rick Price song)|Not a Day Goes By]]\" (February 1992) and the [[Heaven Knows (Rick Price song)|title track]] (July). At the [[APRA Awards (Australia)#Song of the Year|APRA Music Awards]] of 1992 \"Heaven Knows\" won Song of the Year for Price and his co-writer, Heather Field. His second album, contained the single \"[[River of Love (Rick Price song)|River of Love]]\" (April), which peaked at No.&nbsp;18. Since 2009 he has been a resident of [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. He was worked with numerous artists, as a vocalist and songwriter, including [[Tina Arena]], [[Tommy Emmanuel]], [[Mitch Grainger]], [[Irwin Thomas|Jack Jones]], [[Regine Velasquez-Alcasid]] and numerous others. Whilst as a music producer he has worked for [[Girlfriend (band)|Girlfriend]] and [[Dami Im]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/confidential/australian-star-rick-price-set-to-mark-25th-anniversary-of-hit-song--and-one-secret-smash-hit/news-story/5f12c76d8243fc5f41150d99c770|title=Australian star Rick Price is set to mark the 25th anniversary of hit songs and one secret smash|work=The Herald Sun}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRick Allan Price was born on 6 July 1961 in [[Beaudesert, Queensland|Beaudesert]], a small country town {{convert|69|km|mi}} south of [[Brisbane]]. At the age of nine he appeared with his family band, Union Beau, performing at local bush dances in southern Queensland and northern New South Wales.<ref name=\"McFarlane\">{{cite book | last1 = McFarlane | first1 = Ian | authorlink1 = Ian McFarlane | title = Encyclopedia of Australian Rock and Pop | chapter = Encyclopedia entry for 'Rick Price' | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20040419205845/http://www.whammo.com.au/encyclopedia.asp?articleid=650 | chapterurl = http://www.whammo.com.au/encyclopedia.asp?articleid=650 | year = 1999 | publisher = [[Allen & Unwin]] | location = [[St Leonards, New South Wales|St Leonards, NSW]] | archivedate = 19 April 2004 | isbn = 1-86508-072-1 | title-link = Encyclopedia of Australian Rock and Pop }}</ref> Price has cited [[Stevie Wonder]], [[James Taylor]] and [[Carole King]] as his inspirations.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/>\n\nAt the age of 18 Price moved to Sydney where he worked as a session and touring musician, playing bass guitar with various inner city outfits. In September 1983 he was recorded on David Fennell's album ''Harbour Crossing'', where he provided bass guitar and backing vocals.<ref name=\"Foster\">{{cite news | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article116408814 | title = Mostly Jazz: Fennell Back | last = Foster | first = Michael | newspaper = [[The Canberra Times]] | volume = 58 | issue = 17,529 | date = 26 September 1983 | accessdate = 17 September 2016 | page = 12 | via = National Library of Australia}}</ref> During the mid-1980s Price turned more towards his singing. His distinctive vocals were soon in demand \u2013 he was a backing vocalist for [[Marcia Hines]], [[Jon English]], [[Dragon (band)|Dragon]], [[Kerrie Biddell]] and [[Jade Hurley]].<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/><ref name=\"Swift\"/> He joined the Tommy Emmanuel Band during 1988.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/><ref name=\"Holmgren\">[[Australian Rock Database]] entries:\n* Rick Price: {{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130921123454/http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/p/pricerick.html | url = http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/p/pricerick.html | title = Rick Price | last1 = Holmgren | first1 = Magnus | work = hem.passagen.se | publisher = Australian Rock Database (Magnus Holmgren) | archivedate = 21 September 2013 | accessdate = 18 September 2016 }}\n* Tommy Emmanuel Band (1988): {{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130921173236/http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/e/emmanueltommy.html | url = http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/e/emmanueltommy.html | title = Tommy Emmanuel | last1 = Holmgren | first1 = Magnus | first2 = Melody | last2 = Carruthers | work = hem.passagen.se | publisher = Australian Rock Database (Magnus Holmgren) | archivedate = 21 September 2013 | accessdate = 18 September 2016 }}\n</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1988\u20131990: Career beginnings===\nIn 1988 he sang \"Celebration of a Nation\", with Keren Minshull (later a member of [[Euphoria (Australian band)|Euphoria]]), the theme song for the [[Australian Bicentenary]].<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> Price later opined \"That song made me realise I wanted a recording career of my own. I knew I needed a deal but it was also clear to me that before I did that, I had to write songs I was happy with.\"<ref name=\"Leedham\">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article126961373 |title=The new Price is right | last = Leedham | first = Nicole |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=67 |issue=21,060 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=10 December 1992 |accessdate=18 September 2016 |page=21 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He also provided vocals on \"You're not Alone\" (April 1988) by the Australian Olympians \u2013 an ensemble of various local artists \u2013 as a theme song for the national [[1988 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] campaign. It reached the top&nbsp;30 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"AusCharts Not Alone\">{{cite web | url = http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Australian+Olympians&titel=You%27re+Not+Alone&cat=s | title = Australian Olympians \u2013 'You're not Alone' | publisher = Australian Charts Portal. Hung Medien (Steffen Hung) | last = Hung | first = Steffen | accessdate = 18 September 2016 }}</ref> These opportunities helped lay the foundation for his solo career.<ref name=\"Swift\">{{cite web | url = http://www.allmusic.com/artist/rick-price-mn0002838114 | title = Rick Price &#124; Biography & History | last = Swift | first = Brendan | publisher = [[AllMusic]] | accessdate = 17 September 2016 }}</ref> Price began writing his own material in the late 1980s. He was recorded on the single, \"Living Without Your Love\", in 1990, which was written by [[Mike Perjanik]]. It was performed on TV teen soap opera, ''Home and Away'', by a fictitious group, ''Image'', with Price providing lead vocals.\n\n===1991\u20131992: Album ''Heaven Knows''===\n{{Main|Heaven Knows (Rick Price album)}}\nIn 1991 Price signed a deal with [[Sony Music Australia|ColumbiaRecords]] and he travelled to [[Los Angeles]] to work with producer, [[Chris Lord-Alge]] ([[Elton John]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], [[Roxette]]).<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> He issued his debut solo single, \"[[Not a Day Goes By (Rick Price song)|Not a Day Goes By]]\", in February 1992. It was co-written by Price with Pamela Reswick and Steve Werfel.<ref name=\"ASCAP Not\">{{cite web | url = https://mobile.ascap.com/aceclient/AceWeb/#ace/search/title/Not%20a%20Day%20Goes%20By/performer/rick%20price | title = ACE Repertory \u2013 Title: 'Not a Day Goes Past' Performer: Rick Price | publisher = [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] (ASCAP) | accessdate = 18 September 2016 }}</ref> The track was placed on high rotation on radio with the associated music video presented on national TV. It peaked at No.&nbsp;5 and spent 13&nbsp;weeks in the Top&nbsp;40.<ref name=\"AusCharts\">{{cite web | url = http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Rick+Price+%5BAU%5D | title = Discography Rick Price &#91;AU&#93; | publisher = Australian Charts Portal. Hung Medien (Steffen Hung) | last = Hung | first = Steffen | accessdate = 18 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 1992 his second single, \"[[Heaven Knows (Rick Price song)|Heaven Knows]]\", was released.<ref name=\"AusCharts\"/> Price co-wrote that track with Heather Field.<ref name=\"ASCAP Heaven\">{{cite web | url = https://mobile.ascap.com/aceclient/AceWeb/#ace/search/title/Heaven%20Knows/performer/rick%20price | title = ACE Repertory \u2013 Title: 'Heaven Knows' Performer: Rick Price | publisher = American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers (ASCAP) | accessdate = 18 September 2016 }}</ref> It reached No.&nbsp;6.<ref name=\"AusCharts\"/> The song helped launch his international career. In May of that year he joined the ''Wizard of Oz'' show-case in Los Angeles where he performed alongside Tina Arena and other Australian artists. In July, Price released his debut album, ''Heaven Knows'', entered the ARIA Albums Chart at No.&nbsp;3 and stayed in the Top&nbsp;40 chart for nine&nbsp;weeks \u2013 it returned to the Top&nbsp;40 in May of the following year.<ref name=\"AusCharts\"/>\n\nAustralian musicologist, [[Ian McFarlane]], described the album as \"a well-crafted blend of radio-friendly Adult Oriented Rock (AOR), pop and soul material\" where Price had used \"hot US session players who had collectively worked with everyone from [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] to [[Steve Winwood]] and [[Barbra Streisand]].\"<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> It had also been produced by Lord-Alge.<ref name=\"Holmgren\"/> Price explained to Nicole Leedham of ''[[The Canberra Times]]'', \"I could have made the album earlier but I didn't want to go ahead and sign the wrong deal, that can really destroy an artist's career. I also wanted to make sure that I was absolutely happy with every single track on the record.\"<ref name=\"Leedham\"/> To promote the album he formed the Rick Price Band with P. J. Becker on backing vocals, Mike Caen on guitar, Mitch Farmer<!-- Not the footballer --> on drums, Shauna Jensen on backing vocals, Peter Northcote on guitar and Victor Rounds on bass guitar.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/><ref name=\"Holmgren\"/>\n\nIn August ''Heaven Knows'' was released in Europe and Asia, it reached the top&nbsp;100 on the [[GfK Entertainment Charts|German Albums Chart]] in the following February.<ref name=\"GerCharts Heaven\">{{cite web | url = https://www.offiziellecharts.de/album-details-31449 | title =  Rick Price &#91;AU&#93; ''Heaven Knows'' | publisher = [[GfK Entertainment Charts|Offizielle Deutsche Charts]] | language = German | accessdate = 18 September 2016 }}</ref> In September Price embarked on his first solo tour of Australia.<ref name=\"Leedham\"/> He followed with a promotional trip to Europe including the United Kingdom. In October he returned to Europe for further TV appearances and then a three-week promotional trip to [[Southeast Asia]]. By the end of the year his group's line-up was P.J. Becker, Chris Becker on bass guitar, Phil Gildea on guitar, Robert Parde on keyboards and David Porter on drums.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/><ref name=\"Holmgren\"/>\n\nIn November 1992 Price returned to Australia where he, and his co-writer Field, won the Song of the Year category for \"Heaven Knows\" at the [[APRA Awards (Australia)#Song of the Year|APRA Music Awards]].<ref name=\"APRA 92\">{{cite web | url = http://apraamcos.com.au/awards/1990-1999/1992-music-awards/ | title = 1992 APRA Music Award Winners | publisher = [[Australasian Performing Right Association]] (APRA) &#124; [[Australasian Mechanical Copyright Owners Society]] (AMCOS) | year = 1992 | accessdate = 18 September 2016 }}</ref> In December 1992 Price was invited to Germany to perform on a variety show. He then made a 36-hour stopover in [[Metro Manila|Manila]] where he made six TV appearances, two radio interviews and a handful of press.\n\n\"Heaven Knows\" held the top spot in Malaysia for four consecutive weeks while \"Not a Day Goes By\" sat just behind it in the Top 5. In the Philippines, \"Heaven Knows\" sat at number 1 for all of November and December. During this time the album sold over 250,000 units alone in Southeast Asia. Price went on to say, \"It was an exhausting experience, but it was stimulating at the same time. It was all new to me, going to places I'd never been and doing stuff I'd never done, so I certainly didn't get tired of it.\"\n\n===1993\u20131994: Touring and recognition===\nIn January and February 1993, Price once again toured Australia to sold-out venues. In April, he was nominated for 3 [[ARIA Awards]] and on the night performed a tribute to [[Peter Allen (musician)|Peter Allen]] with \"[[Tenterfield Saddler]]\". Later in May, he was asked to perform the song on ''[[Good Morning America]]'' who were in Australia for 2 weeks. The performance was aired to 5 million people. Later that month ''Heaven Knows'' was re-released and included the bonus CD ''Rarities''. Rick spent 2 weeks travelling the country and promoting the re-release performing in acoustic mode.\n\nIn July 1993, ''Heaven Knows'' was released in America and Canada. Back home, Price continued his touring, this time in the Northern Territory and northern Queensland area which he had not previously performed in. The tour was extremely successful, with all shows being theatres and all sold out.\n\nDuring October 1993, Rick performed more concerts in Southeast Asia which incorporated 7 shows in 9 days. They were all sell outs. The [[Sentosa]] Music Festival in [[Singapore]] saw Rick perform in front of 15,000 people. Before returning to Australia, Rick visited Korea for a short promotional and concert tour.\n\nPrice once again joined the ''Wizard of Oz'' show cases in Japan where the album was launched. Whilst in Japan Rick won Song of the Year for \"[[Walk Away Renee]]\" and Album of the Year for ''Heaven Knows'' at the Australian Music Awards. On his return from Japan, Rick was awarded with the 1993 Australian Export Award for recognition of his international success.During the month a new single \"[[Where Is the Love (Roberta Flack and Donny Hathaway song)# Rick Price and Margaret Urlich version|Where Is the Love]]\", a duet with New Zealand musician [[Margaret Urlich]], was released.\n\nIn December 1993, Price was invited to the Singapore Music Awards as a special guest. He picked up Song of the Year for \"Heaven Knows\", then came back home to Australia for more touring before being invited to perform on the numerous [[Carols by Candlelight]] shows around the country and performing \"[[White Christmas (song)|White Christmas]]\". The year was topped off when Price was presented with an Advance Australia Foundation award (in recognition of making an outstanding contribution to the growth and enhancement of Australia and its people)\n\nDuring 1994, Price spent the majority of time writing material for his anticipated follow-up album. From September to December, Price recorded his second album in Melbourne with a host of Australia's leading musicians.\n\n===1995\u20131996: ''Tamborine Mountain''===\n{{Main|Tamborine Mountain (album)}}\nIn April 1995, the long-awaited single \"[[River of Love (Rick Price song)|River of Love]]\" was released, the first from Price's album ''Tamborine Mountain'', which was later released in July. \"It was quite difficult\", Price reveals, \"because I knew it was going to be a different album to ''Heaven Knows''. I made that album as pop as I could make it, I wanted to be certain of airplay and all those kind of things. After the first album was released, I went out and played a lot of acoustic gigs. My audience tripled and people really liked it, which surprised me because I thought it would be a bit too internal, a bit too self conscious. But it worked, which gave me a lot of encouragement and the confidence to write more like that, just simple little stories. And that's the kind of music I've always been drawn to - people like [[James Taylor]] and [[Carole King]], great songwriters who have the ability to say something really simple\".\n\nThe album was produced by Price and American Ben Wisch, who Price was drawn to as a result of his production of [[Marc Cohn]]'s \"[[Walking in Memphis]]\". Special guests on the album include Tommy Emmanuel on guitar and Tina Arena on backing vocals and the duet \"Trust Me This Is Love\".\n\nAfter the success of the first single \"River of Love\", a second single \"Bridge Building Man\" was released. The song is a standout track for Price, written for his father and grandfather. The album title itself is a reference to a small town near [[Beaudesert, Queensland|Beaudesert]] where Price grew up.\n\nIn November and December 1995, following the release of the album, Price then toured with Australia's legendary guitarist Tommy Emmanuel. The tour, Rick Price & Tommy Emmanuel - Together & Alone, was a sell-out. It received rave reviews from critics and the public alike.\n\nIn conjunction with the tour, a third single \"To Be with You\" was released in Australia. Price performed at several Carols by Candlelight shows around the country and continued to tour during early 1996. \"You're Never Alone\", a song Price wrote for his son, was released in Australia while he travelled the country on further promotional tours throughout the remainder of the year.\n\n===1997\u20132003: ''Another Place'' and ''A Million Miles''===\n{{Main|Another Place (Rick Price album)}}\nIn January and February 1997, Price played several shows alongside another accomplished Australian singer/songwriter, Jack Jones. The shows were a huge success with the pair performing their best hits together and alone, proving yet again their abilities as live performers.\n\nFor the majority of the year, Price spent his time in [[Los Angeles]] and [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] writing material for his next album.\n\nSome of the collaborators Price has worked with included Steve Werfel and Pam Reswick on \"Not a Day Goes By\" (who has written songs such as \"[[Chains (Tina Arena song)|Chains]]\" by Tina Arena), [[Jon Lind]] (who has written songs such as \"[[Simple Life (John Farnham song)|Simple Life]]\" by [[John Farnham]], and \"[[Crazy for You (Madonna song)|Crazy for You]]\" by [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]), and [[Randy Goodrum]], a well-respected writer from Nashville. He has also written with Australia's Heather Field who co-wrote \"Heaven Knows\" and \"River of Love\", and once again has worked with Phil Buckle who co-wrote \"What's Wrong With That Girl\" from Rick's ''Heaven Knows'' album.\n\nIn November and December 1997, Price played a couple of showcases to the public with some of the new material he had been working on. During the later months of 1997 and early 1998, Price recorded his new album in Los Angeles. The album ''Another Place'' was released in Australia in July 1999, spanning singles including \"Where in the World\" and \"Good As Gone\". In 2003, parting with Sony, Price released another solo album, ''A Million Miles'', on his own label Clarice. Described as a garage album and going back to his musical roots, he plays every instrument heard on the album.\n\n===2004\u20132011: ''2UP'' and ''Revisited'' and \"John Denver\" tour===\nPrice has spent much of his time writing with, and recording and producing for other artists such as [[Melinda Schneider]], Tamara Stewart, [[Lisa Chappell]] and [[David Franj]]. In 2004, a \"best of\" CD and DVD was released, containing all of Price's bigger hits. In 2007 Price recorded an album with [[Mitch Grainger]] called ''2UP'', featuring acoustic-style covers of such artists as [[Chris Isaac]], and was featured in the soundtrack to the film ''[[December Boys]]''. In 2008, ''Revisited'', an album of his greatest hits recorded in an \"intimate acoustic style\", was released. He toured Tasmania with band Invisible Boy at the year's conclusion.  In 2009, after having relocated to Nashville, Price toured the US with Australian guitar virtuoso Tommy Emmanuel, before returning to Australia and touring in a legacy show to singer-songwriter [[John Denver]], with \"The John Denver Story\".\n\n===2011\u20132016: ''The Waters Edge'' and ''Tennessee Sky''===\n{{Main|The Water's Edge|Tennessee Sky}}\nPrice, having relocated to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] in 2009 toured the US with  guitarist Tommy Emmanuel \nAn album titled ''The Water's Edge'' was released in 2011, featuring the single \"Shape of My Heart\". and \"I'm Coming Home\" as the second single release in 2012. It also includes a cover of the [[Joni Mitchell]] hit \"[[River (Joni Mitchell song)|River]]\". In April 2015, the album ''Tennessee Sky'' was released exclusively though the [[PledgeMusic]] campaign,  where fans could have an input into the production of the album, it was preceded by the first single \"Work That Fire\". The album has been described as an earthy gospel album.<ref name=\"rockclub40\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rockclub40.com/xn/detail/3977244:Note:306057xg_source=activity |title=You're Never Too Old to Rock'nRoll - Welcome to Rock Club 40! |website=Rockclub40.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-07}}</ref>\n''Tennessee Sky'' features an acoustic reworking of the [[Leonard Cohen]] hit \"[[Hallelujah (Leonard Cohen song)|Hallelujah]]\". The album peaked at number 97 in Australia and number 19 on the Australian indie chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.air.org.au/chart/independent_label_album/20150504|title=Independent Label album chart; 4 May 2015|accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref> Price toured the album throughout Victoria Australia in July 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/rick-price-to-tour-victoria-20150420|title=Rick Price To Tour Victoria|website=Noise11.com|date=20 April 2015|accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref> The accompanying tour \"Can I Get A Witness\", was launched on the back of the ''Tennessee Sky'' album release with dates throughout May and June 2016. \n\n===2017\u2013present: ''California Dreaming'' and ''Heaven Knows'' tour===\n{{Main|California Dreaming (Rick Price and Jack Jones album)}}\nIn September 2017, Price released ''California Dreaming'', a collaboration with Australian singer-songwriter [[Irwin Thomas|Jack Jones]]. The album became Price's second top ten album. Price produced [[Dami Im]]'s 2018 album ''[[I Hear a Song (album)|I Hear a Song]]''.\n\nIn May 2018, it was announced Price will tour his album ''Heaven Knows'' in October and November from cover to cover.\n\nIn October 2019, Price released a re-recorded version of \"Nothing Can Stop Us Now\" from ''Tambourine Mountain'' with [[Regine Velasquez|Regine Velasquez-Alcasid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/nothing-can-stop-us-now-single/1483030530|title= Nothing Can Stop Us Now - single with Regine Velasquez-Alcasid |website=iTunes Australia|accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the global APRA Awards in March 2020, Price was awarded the Overseas Recognition Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/tommy-emmanuel-morgan-evans-seaforth-more-honored-at-the-2020-global-apra-music-awards-nashville/american-songwriter/|title= Tommy Emmanuel, Morgan Evans, Seaforth, More Honored at the 2020 Global APRA Music Awards Nashville|website=American Songwriter|date=2 March 2020|accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of albums\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Certifications\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref name=aus>Australian chart peaks:\n*\"You're Not Alone\" ([[Kent Music Report]]) peak: {{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/hH2atw0.jpg|title=Australian ARIA Top 50 Singles Chart \u2013 Week Ending 22nd May, 1988|publisher=Imgur.com (original document published by [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]])|accessdate=7 